<HEADLINE> Roundup: Manila Declares All-Out War Against Crimes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, March 17 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President Fidel Ramos
recently declared an all-out war against organized crimes
including kidnappings, bank robbery, drug trafficking and other
illegal activities in the country.
</P>
<P>
In a handwritten directive issued on March 14, Ramos ordered
Secretary of Interior and Local Governments Robert Barbers to
intensify the anti-kidnap, anti-crime drive by utilizing the
entire criminal justice system.
</P>
<P>
Ramos also ordered the Philippine National Police (PNP), the
Department of National Defense, the Armed Forces of the
Philippines, the Department of Justice and the National Bureau of
Investigation to provide all necessary assistance to Secretary
Barbers.
</P>
<P>
The president told the PNP to disband all private armed groups,
thereby gathering, collecting and accounting for all unlicensed
firearms. He also directed the national police to coordinate more
closely with all intelligence agencies to ensure the success of
the anti-crime campaign.
</P>
<P>
The president also emphasized that he wants a community network
firmly established and mobilized as a preventive strategy in the
campaign against all forms of lawlessness and as a tool for the
arrest and prosecution of criminals.
</P>
<P>
He added the community, one of the pillars of the justice
system, must be tapped in gathering information against kidnappers
and other suspicious characters.
</P>
<P>
President Ramos declared the nationwide war against crimes
after a prestigious magazine of the United States recently
published a story about the seriousness of the kidnapping problem
in the Philippines.
</P>
<P>
Fortune, a publication widely read by executives of the world's
biggest corporations, reported in an article entitled
"Philippines' Kidnapping Problem Spreads" that 241 people were
kidnapped for ransom in 1996, nearly double the official figure a
year before.
</P>
<P>
The figure was estimated 40 times more than in Thailand, a
country with roughly the same population, the story said, adding
that kidnap victims were convinced that some bad military and
police officers are kidnappers themselves or protectors of
kidnappers.
</P>
<P>
Fortune also revealed that wealthy Filipino-Chinese are no
longer the only target to be abducted, Filipinos or foreigners now
are also not immune in the country.
</P>
<P>
Furthermore, the article quoted Philippine Vice President
Joseph Estrada as saying that kidnapping statistics are "greatly
understated" because many victims are too frightened to report to
the police.
</P>
<P>
The story touched off a heated debate in the Philippines. Press
Secretary Hector Villanueva disputed it as "unfair and baseless"
while expressing President Fidel Ramos' resentment at the story.
</P>
<P>
The PNP also flatly denied the report. It said that the crime
rate in the country has dropped by nine percent since 1990,
attracting more foreign investments to spur the growth of the
national economy.
</P>
<P>
Some crime-watch groups, however, said the actual situation in
the country is "much worse" than reported. They revealed that a
total of 179 kidnapping cases happened and 22 of the victims died
last year. For the first two months this year, 41 kidnapping
incidents have been documented.
</P>
<P>
But what is important now is that the Philippine government has
begun to take actions. Following Ramos' order, the Presidential
Anti-crime Commission submitted a bill before the Congress for
approval over the weekend, proposing the passage of a law making
non-reporting of kidnap incidents and non-cooperation on the part
of the victims' families be considered a crime.
</P>
<P>
To stop kidnappings, the bill also recommended imposing
stricter penalty; prohibiting the use of heavily tinted car
windows which are often used by kidnappers as protection; allowing
law enforcers as the only persons authorized to possess or carry
firearms and permitting policemen to arrest kidnapping suspects
even without warrants.
</P>
<P>
The PNP will also hold a consultative meeting on March 20 with
leaders of the Congress and representatives from all walks of life
to map out some key strategies for the coming battle against
crimes.
</P>
<P>
President Ramos' commitment to fighting against crimes received
a warm welcome across the country. The Filipinos expressed
optimism that the Ramos administration would win the war if all
government agencies take concerted and resolute actions.
</P>
</TEXT>
