<HEADLINE> Yeltsin Appoints New First Deputy PM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, March 17 (Xinhua) -- Russian President Boris Yeltsin
appointed Boris Nemtsov, governor of the Nizhny Novgorod region,
the first deputy prime minister today.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin made the offer to 37-year-old Nemtsov when he met him
in the Kremlin, where Yeltsin praised Nemtsov as a man who was
"experienced, had authority and is capable."
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin was expected to announce the revamped government before
he heads to Helsinki, Finland, for a summit with President Clinton
on Thursday and Friday.
</P>
<P>
Nemtsov has won praise as a dynamic governor of the Nizhny
Novgorod region near Moscow, turning the territory into a
laboratory for economic reforms.
</P>
<P>
The area has been used for a variety of pilot projects, with
the World Bank and other international institutions, involving
privatization and enterprise reforms.
</P>
<P>
Nemtsov would handle social welfare policy and the
restructuring of government monopolies such as natural gas and
electricity, Yeltsin said in an interview with several television
networks.
</P>
<P>
With Russia suffering from a host of economic and social
problems, Yeltsin ordered a sweeping government shakeup last
week. But so far, Yeltsin has named only two people to new posts
-- Nemtsov, and Anatoly Chubais, 41, who will also hold the title
of first deputy prime minister.
</P>
<P>
The Russian president asked Nemtsov to join hands with
Chernomyrdin and Chubais to form a young and capable new cabinet.
</P>
<P>
"Two young men -- you and Anatoly Chubais -- create a fresh
young team in the government -- from scratch. No one (else) has
been appointed yet," Yeltsin was quoted by Interfax as saying.
</P>
<P>
Interfax said Nemtsov had accepted the offer and would return
to his home region on the Volga River to make a formal
announcement.
</P>
<P>
Last Friday, Yeltsin announced that the new cabinet would have
only one first deputy prime minister and seven vice-premiers, a
lower rank.
</P>
<P>
His remarks, made during a meeting with media chiefs, were
widely seen as a sign of protracted bargaining between
Chernomyrdin and Chubais over the extent of their control over the
government.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin was due to meet Chernomyrdin and Chubais later Tuesday
to discuss the government reshuffle.
</P>
<P>
Nemtsov was born in October 1959. A physics graduate, he
worked for more than 10 years at a radio and physics institute.
He has been governor of the Nizhny Novgorod region since 1991.
</P>
</TEXT>
