<HEADLINE> Khamenei Announces Makeup of Expediency Committee </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, March 17 (Xinhua) -- Iranian Supreme Leader Ali
Khamenei today announced the new makeup of Iran's Committee to
Determine the Expediency of the Islamic Order headed by President
Akbar Hashemi Rafsanjani.
</P>
<P>
The committee is composed of 25 members, including noted
theologians and high-ranking government officials, the state-run
Tehran Radio reported.
</P>
<P>
The committee is one of the most important and powerful
political organs of the Islamic regime, which was first brought
into existence by the late Iranian spiritual leader Ruhollah
Khomeini in 1988.
</P>
<P>
Observers here noted that the decree announced by Khamenei
could be interpreted into a signal that Rafsanjani's position in
the Islamic regime is confirmed as No. 2 man just after Khamenei
even though Rafsanjani steps down as president after two-term
service in the office this August.
</P>
<P>
The announcement of the new composition of the committee would
also pave the way for Parliament Speaker Ali Akbar Nateq-Nouri
to have greater possibility of winning the 7th presidential
election scheduled for May 23.
</P>
<P>
The committee has the responsibility of arbitrating disputes
between Parliament and the Guardian Council. It also decides
about the general outlines of Iran's domestic and foreign
policies as well as proposing solution for the country's major
problems.
</P>
<P>
In his decree, Khamenei announced his decision to expand the
present makeup of membership of the organ with additional
"officials, statesmen and prominent theologians" to respond to
the needs of Iran at the present time.
</P>
<P>
However, the report gave no details about how many new
members have entered the committee and who have been removed from
it. The appointed 25 members will serve for a period of five
years.
</P>
<P>
Based on the decree, active in the organ are heads of the
three branches of the regime, ranking theologians of the
Guardian Council as well as ministers or directors of government
agencies. 
</P>
</TEXT>
