<HEADLINE> Over 2000 Journalists Gather to Cover US-Russia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Helsinki, March 17 (Xinhua) -- More than 2100 journalists,
technicians are gathering here to cover the summit between U.S.
President Bill Clinton and Russian President Boris Yeltsin here on
March 20-21.
</P>
<P>
Half of the accredited journalists are from the Finnish media,
and the others are from various countries in the world, a Finnish
official told reporters.
</P>
<P>
Nearly 700 news agencies, newspapers, magazines, TV and radios
from around the world will report the historical summit, Antti
Kuusela, first secretary of the Finnish Foreign Ministry, told
Xinhua today.
</P>
<P>
Finland, which hosted the 1990 summit between former Soviet
Union President Mikhail Gorbachev and his then U.S. counterpart
George Bush, spent a budget of nearly five million Finnish marks
(about one million U.S. dollars) solely for the press covering
Yeltsin-Clinton summit.
</P>
<P>
Ilkka Rautakivi, a technician for the summit, told Xinhua that
40 kilometers optical fiber cables have been installed for the
press.
</P>
<P>
He said that more than 1,000 mobile telephones will be provided
for three press centers, one of which is specially for TV and
radios. At least 70 pentium-200HZ computers are free for
journalists to use.
</P>
<P>
The presidential summit, the 11th between presidents of Russia
and the U.S., had been scheduled on Wednesday and Thursday, but
postponed one day later due to Clinton's knee injury.
</P>
<P>
The summit was described by Western media as a meeting between
two "invalids". Clinton will be on crutches or in a wheelchair to
the summit while Yeltsin just recovered from his heart by-pass
surgery. The summit was widely regarded as the most important one
between Russia and the U.S. after the end of the Cold War since it
may open a new chapter of the U.S.-Russian relations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
