<HEADLINE> Cambodian First PM Warning About King's Abdication </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PHNOM PENH, March 17 (Xinhua) -- Cambodia's First Prime
Minister, Prince Norodom Ranariddh, warned today that if King
Norodom Sihanouk really abdicates, Cambodia will plunge into
trouble.
</P>
<P>
Ranariddh said: "I have repeated many times that if my father
abdicates, there will be trouble in the political situation in
Cambodia."
</P>
<P>
Ranariddh described the King's intended abdication as
"unrealistic," and said he "does not believe it."
</P>
<P>
King Sihanouk made his intention of abdication known in a
bulletin released by the royal palace on February 26. It said he
was "seriously envisaging abdicating without intending to go to
live in another country."
</P>
<P>
The Prince also said if the King gave up the throne, his
Funcinpec party would have no choice but to join the King.
"Ninety percent of people in the country will join him," he added.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the General Elections scheduled for 1998,
Ranariddh said that "nobody has the right to cancel them."
</P>
<P>
"Only a two-thirds majority vote by the National Assembly can
decide whether to postpone or cancel the elections," he said.
</P>
<P>
Second Prime Minister Hun Sen said Saturday that if the King
abdicated from the throne, both regional and national elections
must be cancelled. 
</P>
</TEXT>
