<HEADLINE> Hanoi Court Sentences Canadian Woman to Death for Drugs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, March 17 (Xinhua) -- A Canadian woman was sentenced to
death and her Vietnamese mother was jailed for life by a Hanoi
court today for trafficking in heroin.
</P>
<P>
Nguyen Thi Hiep, a 40-year-old naturalized Canadian and her
71-year-old mother, Tran Thi Cam, were arrested last April at
Hanoi airport as they checked in for a flight to Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
They were carrying 5.45 kilograms of heroin, packed in small
bags and hidden behind five lacquer paintings in their luggage,
court officials said.
</P>
<P>
The court also fined the 40-year-old Canadian woman one billion
dong (86,000 U.S. dollars) and her 70-year-old mother 500 million
dong (43,000 dollars).
</P>
<P>
The two had 15 days to appeal against the sentences.
</P>
<P>
Under Vietnamese law, trafficking with as little as one
kilogram of heroin is punishable by death.
</P>
<P>
Hiep, who was reported by local newspapers to have left Vietnam
in 1982 and gained Canadian nationality in 1985, is the fourth
foreigner to receive the death sentence for drug-related crimes in
Vietnam. 
</P>
</TEXT>
