<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Record 561 Foreign Banks Have Branches in London </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, March 17 (Xinhua) -- The number of foreign banks in
London continued to increase sharply in 1996, with a record total
of 561 having branches, subsidiaries or representative offices,
reflecting the growth of London as a financial center.
</P>
<P>
An annual survey by Noel Alexander, a London-based banking
consultancy, showed that there was a net increase of 20 overseas
banks in London last year, with 16 leaving and 36 moving in.
</P>
<P>
There were 14 overseas banks which opened substantial
operations, meaning branches or subsidiaries as opposed to
representative offices, last year compared with eight in 1995.
</P>
<P>
Growth was particularly strong among European banks, with 28
moving in and seven moving out.
</P>
<P>
There was also a sharp influx of Russian banks, nine of which
opened representative offices in 1996, with only two leaving the
city.
</P>
<P>
The number of US banks is slowly increasing once again after a
decline in the 1980s, with Prudential-Bache International opening
operations here last year and shifting its overseas headquarters
to London from Luxembourg.
</P>
<P>
The survey said that among the 561 foreign banks now in London,
53 are US and 249 are European. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970318.0015 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Approves German, France EMU Plans </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, March 17 (Xinhua) -- European Union finance ministers
on Monday approved German and French economic convergency plans
and reaffirmed their belief that the Economic and Monetary
Union(EMU) would start on time in 1999.
</P>
<P>
"They were both convincing to their colleagues that they would
meet the goals of the EMU convergence criteria," Dutch finance
minister Gerrit Zalm told a news conference.
</P>
<P>
The ministers, facing mounting speculation of a delay to the
launch of a single currency, had been considering the credibility
of the two countries' EMU plans.
</P>
<P>
Their meeting comes amid record unemployment in Germany, and
doubts over whether Bonn itself could strictly adhere to the
budgetary targets outlined in the Maastricht Treaty.
</P>
<P>
"Both programs are based on realistic and credible
assumptions," EU Commissioner for monetary affairs Yves-Thibault
de Silguy said.
</P>
<P>
Germany and France also assured the other 13 EU countries their
commitment to take additional measures in case they stray from
their budgetary plan during 1997, the year when they will be
judged for EMU fitness.
</P>
<P>
The new German convergence plan provides for average GDP(Gross
Domestic Product) growth of 2.5 percent, inflation of 1.5 percent
and a 6.2 percent yield on long-term government bonds.
</P>
<P>
As concerns the budget deficit, German authorities are
determined to bring it down to 2.5 percent of GDP in 1998 and 1.5
percent in 2000.
</P>
<P>
De debt, meanwhile, will reach something like 60 percent of
GDP. In 1997, it will hit 61.5 percent, compared to 60.2 percent
in 1996. During the following years, the German debt is expected
to fall and to reach 59.7 percent in 2000.
</P>
<P>
The French program assumes GDP growth of 2.3 percent in 1997
and 2.5 percent on an annual basis between 1998 and 2001.
</P>
<P>
It also includes a 3.0 percent deficit-to-GDP target and sees
outstanding government debt slightly below 60 percent of output.
</P>
<P>
Countries wishing to join the EMU will be judged on their 1997
economic performance, the details of which will not be known until
in the spring next year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
