<DOCNO> XIE19970318.0016 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwean Women Still Marginalized: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, March 17 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe will not develop as long
as women are marginalized and denied access to land and credit to
start their own businesses, a senior government official has
said.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a function to celebrate International Women's Day
on Sunday, Secretary for National Affairs, Employment Creation
and Cooperatives Ministry Tendai Bare-Machirori said there is
need to intensify efforts to economically empower women and
eradicate poverty in the country.
</P>
<P>
She said since women constitute more than half of Zimbabwe's
population of 11 million people, they are an important human
resource base and excluding them from positions of power would
retard development of society.
</P>
<P>
She said her ministry would soon come up with a three-year
project to help women enter politics.
</P>
<P>
The project is aimed at increasing participation of all women
in political life, and particular focus would be on this year's
urban females to pave the way for the general elections in the
year 2000. 
</P>
</TEXT>
