<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe, S. Africa Agree on Duty Status </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, March 17 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe and South Africa have
agreed to scrap duty on most agricultural exports, paving the way
for increased exports by Zimbabwe to its largest trading partner.
</P>
<P>
Co-Chairman of the Agricultural Committee formed last year to
negotiate tariffs on all primary agricultural products, Dave
Hasluck said today it was agreed Zimbabwe would have duty-free
access to such products as beef, poultry, pork and mutton.
</P>
<P>
However, such agricultural products as vegetables, cut flowers
and sub-tropical fruits were excluded from the agreement because
they did not fall within the 1964 trade pact which Zimbabwe and
South Africa were currently re-negotiating.
</P>
<P>
Hasluck said three agreements -- on tariffs, phytosanitary
arrangements and veterinary controls -- had been reached by the
Agricultural Committee and these should be ready for submission
for formal signing before the end of this month. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
