<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Recorded Crime Figures in UK Show 4th Fall in Row </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, March 17 (Xinhua) -- The total number of recorded
crimes in Britain fell 1.3 percent last year, the fourth drop in a
row, but violent crime rose 11 percent, according to the Home
Office Monday.
</P>
<P>
Police recorded 5,033,800 crimes in 1996 compared with
5,100,200 the year before, Home Office figures reveal today.
</P>
<P>
Home Secretary Michael Howard said the figures showed the tide
of rising crime was turning and underlined the ruling Conservative
Party's reputation for being tough on crime.
</P>
<P>
However, the main opposition Labor Party claimed that crime had
actually doubled since the Conservatives came to power in 1979.
And the Liberal Democratic Party also accused Tories of cutting
the number of police.  
</P>
</TEXT>
