<BODY>
<HEADLINE> All Is Ready for All-Africa Trade Fair, Nigeria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, March 17 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria today urged countries in
the world to participate in the All-African Trade Fair it will
host at the end of this month, saying that all preparations have
been made.
</P>
<P>
Rear Admiral Jibrila Ayinla, Minister of Commerce and Tourism,
announced here that all facilities are ready at the Kaduna
International Trade Fair Complex in northern Nigeria for the
event, which is jointly sponsored by the Organization of African
Unity (OAU) and African Economic Community (AEC).
</P>
<P>
The organizing committee under the ministry has made
significant progress in areas, like logistics and protocol,
provision of medical facilities, security and publicity, for the
successful hosting of the fair, he said.
</P>
<P>
The fair, officially known as the 7th OAU/AEC All-Africa Trade
and Tourism Fair, is aimed at providing a forum for the exchange
and dissemination of information on intro-African trade.
</P>
<P>
"It is believed that the potential for intra-Africa trade can
be immediately developed by concerted efforts to exchange facts,
ideas and existing resources through an appropriate forum like
the one provided by the All-Africa Trade Fair," the minister
said.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, "as big brother, Nigeria should pull other African
countries along together to boost trade and tourism," he told
newsmen at a forum.
</P>
<P>
According to the minister, 20 OAU member states and about 100
multi-national companies, including such big company as General
Motors of the United States, have booked their stands at the
fair. Some of them are installing pavilions for their exhibits.
</P>
<P>
He called on all OAU member states, the international business
community and collaborating international agencies to "actively
and effectively" participate in the fair, which will be declared
open by Nigeria's Head of State General Sani Abacha on March 29.
</P>
<P>
The OAU Council of Ministers has formally passed a 12-point
resolution urging all member states to effectively participate in
the fair, he said.
</P>
<P>
The fair, held once every four years, was approved by OAU
Council of Ministers at its ninth ordinary session in Kinshasa,
Zaire, in 1967. The last one was held in Bulawayo, Zimbabwe, in
1992.
</P>
<P>
Due to some problems in preparations, this fair was postponed
from November last year to between March 29 and April 6 this
year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
