<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe on Alert for Letter Bombs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, March 17 (xinhua) -- Zimbabwe's Posts and
Telecommunications Corporation (PTC) has been put on alert for
letter bombs allegedly being sent to U.S. targets throughout the
world including Zimbabwe, the Sunday Mail reported today.
</P>
<P>
The letter bombs are believed to be coming from Egyptian
terrorists but an official at the Egyptian embassy in Harare said
joint efforts by Egyptian and American security agents to trace
the origin of the letters in Cairo were not successful.
</P>
<P>
He said this was being done by people bent on tarnishing
Egypt. "But these people are forging Egyptian stamps and postal
marks. It's very easy to forge these things and make them appear
authentic. Evidence shows that nothing was coming out of Cairo,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
However, he confirmed that the letter bombs were being
targeted at Americans and most of the bombs were sent to New York
and one had exploded at a New York newspaper office, injuring two
people who were trying to open or examine the letters.
</P>
<P>
Senior officials within the PTC confirmed to the Sunday Mail
that a warning has been sent out by the Switzerland-based
Universal Postal Union for all postal centers to look out for the
letter bombs.
</P>
<P>
The PTC security department has been on alert and all mail
with Egyptian postal marks or stamps is being treated with
extreme caution and subjected to "extensive security testing",
they said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
