<HEADLINE> Air Zimbabwe Pilots Continue Strike </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, March 17 (Xinhua) -- The strike by Air Zimbabwe pilots
and flight engineers entered its fourth day today with passengers
continuing to be inconvenienced by disrupted flights.
</P>
<P>
Air Zimbabwe spokesman David Mwenga said today the four leased
aircraft from South africa continued to carry passengers to most
of the local and regional destinations while the London flight
remained canceled since the start of the strike last Friday.
</P>
<P>
"So far there has been no progress on the strike and the team
comprising members of the airline's management and striking
pilots and flight engineers has not been set up yet," he said.
</P>
<P>
The estimated 70 pilots and flight engineers are demanding
higher salaries and perks.
</P>
<P>
It is understood that they are demanding an annual salary of
about 350,000 Zimbabwe Dollars (31,818 U.S. Dollars), excluding
allowances for a captain.
</P>
<P>
The airline's management said it cannot, at this stage, afford
the increments due to the low profits the airline had made.
</P>
