<HEADLINE> Mubarak Attacks Netanyahu's Settlement Policy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, March 17 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak
today expressed his indignation at the Israeli settlement policy
which "has gravely jeopardized the peace process".
</P>
<P>
In an interview here with the American B.B.S. network, carried
by the Egyptian T.V., the president warned continuation of the
Israeli policy would not lead to just peace but would rather
provoke violence and absolutely grave consequences.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian-Israeli negotiations have virtually frozen over
the recent Israeli decisions to build 6,500 Jewish homes in East
Jerusalem and withdraw from only 9 percent of the West Bank in the
first stage of further pullback, falling far less than 30 percent
Palestinians had demanded at the moment.
</P>
<P>
"I think that things are plunging," Mubarak said, demanding the
Israelis' commitment to the pledges they made and the agreements
they signed with the Palestinian National Authority.
</P>
<P>
"I had asked all Israeli leaders including Netanyahu and his
predecessors Shimon Peres and Yitzhak Rabin not to ignore the
great significance of Jerusalem," he added.
</P>
<P>
Asked whether he sympathizes with Netanyahu who was subject to
strong criticism by hardliners in his coalition government during
the talks on Hebron, Mubarak said peace is much more important
than "the ongoings in the Israeli coalition."
</P>
<P>
Mubarak said that he would resign if he were in the same
predicament faced by Israeli Prime Minister Binyamin Netanyahu,
whose policies have enraged the Arab world and failed to pacify
the hardliners.
</P>
<P>
"If I were in his place and found troubles with the
right wingers and opposition to the agreements signed by previous
Israeli government, I would have resigned," he said. "Peace will
continue with or without Netanyahu," he added.
</P>
<P>
After meeting Jordanian King Hussein Sunday night, Netanyahu
vowed to stick to its plans to begin building the Jewish
neighborhood this week in Arab East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
While ruling out the possibility of convening an Arab summit at
this moment, Mubarak said the Al-Quds(Jerusalem) Committee will
hold a meeting chaired by King Hassan II of Morocco in Rabat this
month.
</P>
<P>
On talks between Syria and Israel, the president told the
American network that these talks started and continued during the
Rabin and Peres governments because Syrians felt that the Israelis
respect their agreements with the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
But the current negative developments have eaten into the
trust, he said, adding that Syria is ready to restart talks from
the point they stopped in the previous rounds. 
</P>
</TEXT>
