<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UK Crimes Total at Twice Official Level: Survey </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, March 17 (Xinhua) -- The real number of crimes
committed in Britain is at nearly twice the level suggested by
official figures, according to a latest survey conducted by MORI
for the magazine, Reader's Digest.
</P>
<P>
The survey, based on interviews with just over 2,000 people all
over the country, estimated that the genuine total number of
offences is around 10 million, compared with the official figures,
which in recent years have put it at just over five million.
</P>
<P>
The survey was released just before the Home Office's
announcement of the figures for 1996 on Monday, which it said
stood at 5,033,800, a fall of 1.3 percent compared with the year
before and the fourth drop in a row.
</P>
<P>
However, the survey said that despite the falling figures,
almost nine out of 10 people surveyed said their concern about
crime had increased in recent years.
</P>
<P>
About 47 percent of those interviewed said they had been
victims of crime in the past year, and 44 percent of those had
failed to report it.
</P>
<P>
They told the survey they had not reported crimes because they
did not think the police would do anything about it, had no
confidence that the criminals would be caught, or because they
felt the offences were too trivial. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970318.0033 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-18 </DATE_TIME>
