<HEADLINE> Henkel Posts Record Profits in 1996 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, March 17 (Xinhua) -- Germany's chemicals and detergents
company Henkel today reported record profits in 1996, which
reached 515 million marks (303 million U.S. dollars), and expected
further growth in 1997 with the help of newly-acquired U.S. firm.
</P>
<P>
The figure was up six percent over the record set in 1995, with
turnover increasing by 15 percent to 16.3 billion marks, reports
reaching here said.
</P>
<P>
Overseas sales totaled 10.8 billion marks, up 19 percent from
1995, with highest growth being reported in Asia and Australia, at
56 percent, followed by Latin America, 35 percent.
</P>
<P>
Hans-Dietrich Winkhaus, chairman of the Duesseldorf-based
company, attributed increased turnover to the results of
newly-acquired cosmetics company Schwarzkopf in Hamburg.
</P>
<P>
He also hoped that the new U.S. acquisitions, Loctite and
Novamax Technologies, would bring Henkel profits up to a new
record in 1997. Their results will be included in Henkel turnover
this year for the first time.
</P>
<P>
In the first two months this year, Henkel had already
registered both sales and profits growth, according to him.
</P>
</TEXT>
