<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Africans Speak Between 1,250 and 2,100 Languages </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, March 17 (Xinhua) -- Africans today speak between
1,250 and 2,100 languages and dialects, according to a press
release issued here today by the United Nations Educational,
Scientific and Cultural Organization (UNESCO).
</P>
<P>
Linguistic scholars and governmental experts representing more
than 45 African countries are advocating strategies for
multi-lingual educational and cultural policies at a
UNESCO-organized conference convened from March 17 to 21 in
Harare, Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
The release said the five-day inter-governmental conference on
linguistic policies in Africa will critically evaluate national
policies and the obstacles multi-lingualism can pose on
education, health, communication and development in Africa.
</P>
<P>
Referring to African languages, the release said: "Cameroun's
eight million citizens share 185, an average of 50,000 speakers
per language," adding that about 410 languages are spoken in
Nigeria, 206 in Zaire and 97 in Ethiopia.
</P>
<P>
At the other extreme, the release noted, more than 90 percent
of the populations in Botswana (Tswana), Lesotho (Sotho),
Madagascar (Malgache) or Somalia (Somali) share a common
language.
</P>
<P>
Participants at the conference will evaluate language policies
and practices and highlight experiences in multi-lingual
societies, including those outside Africa.
</P>
<P>
"They will also propose regional and sub-regional cooperation
projects and recommend strategies to better integrate
multi-lingualism into political, educational and cultural life,"
the release said.
</P>
<P>
It added that following the meeting of experts, African
ministers will meet in Harare from March 20 to 21 to examine a
final report and adopt a declaration on linguistic policy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
