<DOCNO> XIE19970318.0036 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Paper: Mercedes Seeks to Triple Business in Asia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, March 17 (Xinhua) -- Germany's luxury carmaker
Mercedes-Benz AG is seeking to triple its business in Asia over
the next 10 years, the Berlin daily Die Welt reported today.
</P>
<P>
Citing internal company documents, the newspaper said Mercedes
aims to achieve annual sales turnover of 15 billion marks (8.8
billion U.S. dollars) in the Asian region by the year 2006.
</P>
<P>
In 1995, the company sold 87,900 cars there, totaling about
5.2 billion marks.
</P>
<P>
Peter Fietzek, a Mercedes manager, told Die Welt that Asia,
particularly China, was considered as a region of growth for the
company. However, Mercedes sold only 1,500 passenger cars and 800
commercial vehicles on the Chinese market in 1996, short of
expected sales volume of 3,000 units.
</P>
<P>
The company is currently shifting its emphasis towards the sale
of commercial vehicles in the region. Its share now of the
regional market for commercial vehicles is less than one percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
