<HEADLINE> Arafat Condemns Israel's Har Homa Building Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, March 17 (Xinhua) -- Palestinian National Authority
(PNA) President Yasser Arafat today once again condemned the
Israeli government's decision to go ahead with the construction
of a new Jewish neighborhood in East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
Arafat said that Israel's insistence on building new Jewish
homes in Har Homa (Jabal Abu Ghneim) on the southeastern outskirts
of Jerusalem "violates the signed accords and contradicts the
Middle East peace process."
</P>
<P>
The PNA president was speaking at a press conference following
talks with Jordan's Crown Prince Hassan Ibn Talal and Prime
Minister Abdul Karim Kabariti, who arrived in Gaza this morning.
</P>
<P>
Hassan's visit to the Gaza Strip today was set up in phone
conversation between King Hussein of Jordan and Arafat Sunday
while the king was meeting with Israeli Prime Minister Binyamin
Netanyahu in Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
For his part, Hassan warned at the press conference against
the danger of renewal of violence in the region, and urged Israel
to understand that there was no alternative to peace.
</P>
<P>
Arafat praised what he called "the Jordanian initiative to
rescue the peace process."
</P>
<P>
On Sunday, Hussein paid a condolence visit to the families of
the seven school girls who were shot dead by a Jordanian soldier
in Naharayim in the Jordan Valley Thursday.
</P>
<P>
He also visited a girl pupil and a teacher who were injured
during the shooting incident, at Hadassah Hospital in Jerusalem,
as well as President Ezer Weizman, who underwent surgery
Friday after a fall.
</P>
<P>
During his meeting with Netanyahu, King Hussein arranged a
phone call to Arafat, which, in fact, resumed contacts between
Israel and the Palestinians following disputes over the Har Homa
settlement and other issues.
</P>
<P>
It was also agreed at the phone conversation that Arafat could
fly his plane in and out of the Dahaniya Airport in the Gaza Strip
without special permission from Israel.
</P>
<P>
It was believed that Hassan had carried an important message
today from King Hussein to Arafat on the current situation in the
region, following the visit by Hussein to Israel Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Palestinian officials said that there was an attempt to set up
a three-way meeting between Arafat, Hussein and Netanyahu in the
coming days, which is aimed at resolving differences between
them. 
</P>
