<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cameroun Launches Campaign Against Female </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YAOUNDE, March 17 (Xinhua) -- Cameroun's Minister of Social
and Women's Affairs Aissatou Yaou launched here today a
campaign against female circumcision.
</P>
<P>
According to the World Health Organization (WHO), sponsor of
the campaign, female circumcision is a major problem affecting
the lives of more than 100 million girls and women in Africa. It
is practised in 27 out of the 46 African countries where WHO
operates.
</P>
<P>
Though not a disease, female circumcision, which partially or
totally removes the clitoris or other sexual organs of a girl, is
considered as a form of violence against women as it causes
excessive bleeding, serious infections, painful or risky delivery
and even death.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, in case of group circumcision, the risk of HIV
infection are very high.
</P>
<P>
The minister also called for all women in Cameroun to condemn
female circumcision and to improve women's life.
</P>
<P>
Female circumcision exists mainly in the southwestern and the
extreme northern regions in Cameroun, and constitute a serious
health problem in most African countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
