<HEADLINE> EU Threatens to Withhold Investment in Zambia's </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, March 17 (Xinhua) -- An envoy of the European Union
(EU) threatened here today to withhold its additional financial
investment in the wildlife and tourism sector of Zambia if
nothing is done to "unsuitable tourism developments" in Zambia.
</P>
<P>
Head of a delegation of the European Commission Charles Brook
made the warning at the opening of a five-day logical framework
analysis workshop on development of a sustainable wildlife
management system project.
</P>
<P>
He said that at present there is an acute danger of
indiscriminate exploitation of the wildlife estates, exacerbated
by accelerating population growth and proliferation of sometimes
unsuitable tourism developments.
</P>
<P>
If an effective management system is put in place, Zambia will
be in a position to seek additional investment, said Brook.
</P>
<P>
The European Union has been financially and materially
assisting the Department of National Parks and Wildlife Service
of Zambia.
</P>
<P>
At the workshop, Zambian Tourism Minister Amusaa Mwanamwambwa
said the Zambian government is committed to seeing that the
restructuring and re-organization of the wildlife sector succeed.
</P>
