<HEADLINE> Irish Defense Minister Inspects Troops in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, March 17 (Xinhua) -- Irish Defense Minister Sean
Barrett inspected today the Irish contingent in the U.N. Interim
Force in Lebanon (UNIFIL) at the Irish battalion's headquarters
in Tibnine, Bint Jbeil, in south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Barrett, accompanied by General Gerald MacMahon, the Irish
army's chief of staff, and Kenneth Thompson, the Middle East
consultant to the Irish foreign ministry, attended a ceremony of
awarding medals to a number of officers and soldiers.
</P>
<P>
The Irish delegation arrived in south Lebanon Sunday to
celebrate Ireland's National Day with the 80-member Irish troops
taking part in the peacekeeping missions in south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
After a parade, the Irish defense minister addressed his
battalion, saying that a rapid change of the situation has been
witnessed in Lebanon since the UNIFIL was established in 1978.
</P>
<P>
He said that the Lebanese people and the Lebanese authorities
have shown a "strong desire" to develop their national army in all
parts of south Lebanon, and the UNIFIL is supported by the
Lebanese authorities in order to fulfill its basical missions.
</P>
<P>
The Irish defense minister noted that the UNIFIl is widely
accepted in the region.
</P>
<P>
Major General Stanislaw Franciszek Wozniak, commander of the
UNIFIL, and Timor Goksel, spokesman of the international force,
attended the ceremony.
</P>
<P>
The UNIFIL, comprising contingents from Fiji, Finland, France,
Ghana, Ireland, Italy, Nepal, Norway and Poland, was set up in
March 1978 after Israel's first invasion into Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
U.N. Secretary General Kofi Annan recommended another six-month
extension of the 4,500-strong U.N. peacekeeping force's mandate
in January 1997. 
</P>
