<HEADLINE> Meningitis Kills 100 in N. Ghana </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, March 17 (Xinhua) -- At least 100 people were killed
after meningitis broke out in northern Ghana since the beginning
of the year, said a report reaching here today.
</P>
<P>
The situation has been worsened due to shortage of vaccine
there, the report said, quoting medical workers in Accra, capital
of Ghana.
</P>
<P>
In the Upper East Region alone, about 80 people have died so
far this year, and the viral disease particularly hit the
regional capital of Bawku, 830 km north of Accra.
</P>
<P>
In Koforidua, a town 85 km north of the regional capital, six
people were killed by cerebro-spinal meningitis (CSM) after an
infected woman traveled from Bawku to attend a funeral.
</P>
<P>
Last weekend, Health Minister Eunice Brookman-Amissah went to
Bawku with Defense Minister Alhaji Mahama Iddrisu in an air force
jet, carrying vaccines and mattresses, the report said.
</P>
<P>
According to the health minister, the World Health
Organization has so far supplied 250,000 CSM vaccines, out of a
required three million.
</P>
<P>
The viral disease has struck earlier than expected, the
minister added.
</P>
<P>
Some 140 cases have been recorded in the Upper West Region
since January 1, said Regional Public Health Director Francis
Banka who recalled that the disease had claimed 15 lives out of
81 in the same period last year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
