<HEADLINE> Lebanon's Army Stresses Coordination With Syria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, March 17 (Xinhua) -- The Lebanese army reiterated
today a coordination with the "brotherly Syrian Arab army" in
confronting any possible Israeli aggression against this country,
and accused the Jewish state of shaking Lebanon's stability.
</P>
<P>
In a directive to its officers and soldiers, the Lebanese army
command noted that Israel is still following "sabotaging plans" by
various means in order to isolate Lebanon and to separate the
Lebanese and the Syrian tracks.
</P>
<P>
The full text of the directive was carried this evening by the
state-run Lebanese National News Agency.
</P>
<P>
The army command underlined that its eye is "always open" and
it "is conscious of the real situation and is coordinating with
the brotherly Syrian Arab army in confronting any possible
Israeli aggression."
</P>
<P>
It accused Israel of "always attempting to shake the stability
and the internal unity in Lebanon."
</P>
<P>
About one year has passed since a suspension of the peace
talks on the Lebanon-Israeli and the Syrian-Israeli tracks, the
command noted.
</P>
<P>
During this period and especially after the Israeli Likud
government taking power, it added, the Jewish state has
witnessedly "gone backward in the peace process and has broken its
promises and agreements of principle it previously reached" with
Arab states.
</P>
<P>
As far as Lebanon concerned, the directive pointed out, Israel
"has not hidden its intentions toward Lebanon and its sabotaging
plans against Lebanon."
</P>
<P>
"Israel is still making efforts by various means in a purpose
to isolate Lebanon and to separate the Syrian and Lebanese tracks
from each other," the command said, putting the so-called Lebanon
First" proposal raised by Israel as an example.
</P>
<P>
Beirut has argued that the "Lebanon First," put forward by the
Likud government after taking power in June 1996, was aimed at
"driving a wedge" between Lebanon and Syria.
</P>
<P>
Lebanon upholds an interlock of the Lebanese and Syrian
tracks, and refuses to sign a separate peace agreement with
Israel before Syria does so. 
</P>
</TEXT>
