<HEADLINE> Israeli, Palestinian Negotiators Meet In </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, March 17 (Xinhua) -- Israeli and Palestinian
officials met here this evening in an attempt to get the
troublous negotiations back on track, according to a report of
the state-run Israel Radio.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Cabinet Secretary Danny Naveh and Palestinian National
Authority (PNA) Minister of Local Government Saeb Erekat
discussed, among other things, an arrangement of a summit
between Israeli Prime Minister Binyamin Netanyahu and
Palestinian President Yasser Arafat.
</P>
<P>
Today's talks came following an intervention by King Hussein
of Jordan in the stalled Israeli-Palestinian talks during a
visit here Sunday.
</P>
<P>
During his meeting with Netanyahu, Hussein arranged a phone
call with Arafat, which resulted in the resumption of contacts
between the negotiators of the two sides.
</P>
<P>
Early in the afternoon, Israeli Defense Minister Yitzhak
Mordechai and Palestinian Minister of Planning and International
Cooperation Nabil Sha'ath met in Tel Aviv. They agreed that
Arafat could fly his plane in and out of the Dahaniya Airport in
Gaza without special permission from Israel. Until now his plane
would take off from Egyptian territory.
</P>
<P>
However, overall agreement on general operation of the airport
is still to be reached. Israel demands security control for the
facility.
</P>
<P>
Sha'ath told reporters after the meeting that the arrangement
for President Arafat's flights is a small, but an important
one. He hoped that the airport will be opened up very soon,
adding that conclusion of an agreement on its utilization for
all passengers and cargo is very important for the Palestinian
people and their economy.
</P>
<P>
Mordechai made it clear that there was no connection between
today's achievement and other outstanding issues.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Foreign Minister David Levy said in an interview with
Israel Radio today that Netanyahu and Arafat would probably meet
this week. He said that the construction of New Jewish homes in
Har Homa in East Jerusalem should not affect the meeting.
</P>
<P>
The groundwork of the Har Homa settlement is expected to
begin in a couple of days. But the Palestinians would not budge
in its opposition to the construction. 
</P>
</TEXT>
