<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cyprus Welcomes EU Decision on Accession </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, March 17 (Xinhua) -- The Cypriot government considered
"positive" a European Union (EU) Council decision concerning
accession talks, Government Spokesman Yiannakis Cassoulides said
here today.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the decision reaffirming the start of accession
talks with Cyprus, made by the EU Ministerial Council in Apeldorn
of the Netherlands on Sunday, Cassoulides told his daily press
briefing that Cyprus' course to the EU is "irreversible."
</P>
<P>
EU Council decided two years ago that EU accession talks with
Cyprus will begin six months after the end of the
Intergovernmental Conference.
</P>
<P>
But some EU members has preferred to a Cyprus solution before
accession talks. Last month, Germany, Britain and France made a
proposal that the Turkish Cypriots should participate in the
EU-Cyprus accession talks, which was rejected by the Cypriot
government.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman pointed out that the relevant EU decision of
March 6, 1995 does not consider a Cyprus solution as a
precondition for the island's EU membership.
</P>
<P>
However, he noted that "accession negotiations would be less
complicated and easier if a solution were reached beforehand."
</P>
<P>
He said that Cyprus could facilitate the improvement of
Greco-Turkish relations as well as EU-Turkish relations.
</P>
<P>
Earlier today, Foreign Minister Alecos Michaelides said last
Sunday's EU Council decision "will facilitate to a significant
extent our course to Europe."
</P>
<P>
The Apeldorn meeting also urged Turkey to show flexibility
in the Cyprus question to overcome the obstacles for closer
ties between Turkey and the EU, as called for in the customs
union agreement the EU has concluded with Turkey.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus, divided since the 1974 Turkish invasion, applied for
full EU membership in 1990. 
</P>
</TEXT>
