<HEADLINE> 2 Former T.V. Officials to Stand Trial in Egypt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, March 17 (Xinhua) -- Two former leading Egyptian media
officials will be tried soon on charges of corruption and taking
bribes, the Egyptian Administrative Prosecution decided today.
</P>
<P>
Mamdouh el-Leithy, an influential script writer and former
chairman of the Egyptian T.V. Media Production Sector, will stand
trial on April 2 before the Supreme Disciplinary Court.
</P>
<P>
The prosecution has found Leithy involved in a series of
financial violations, including accepting a Mercedes car from a
Saudi prince, whose family owns an Arabic satellite TV network,
the Egyptian MENA news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The former T.V. boss, under fire by an indictment sheet
including 26 charges, was also being investigated on suspicion of
earning 317,000 Egyptian pounds (109,000 U.S. dollars) from
contracts he signed in 1992-96 as head of the production sector.
</P>
<P>
Amin Bassiouni, former chairman of the Egyptian Radio and
T.V. Union's Board of Trustees, was referred along with Leithy to
the General Prosecution for financial violations. 
