<HEADLINE> Le Pen Asks Court to Hold Controversial Book </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, March 17 (Xinhua) -- Jean-Marie Le Pen, the president of
France's extreme-right National Front (FN) party, has asked the
15th Tribunal of Grand Instance of Paris to impose prior restraint
on the book "Roman d'un President", announced today its
publisher Librairie Plon.
</P>
<P>
In this biography of President Jacques Chirac written by
journalists Maurice Szafran and Nicolas Domenach, Le Pen was
quoted as saying that Chirac was taken hostage by Jews, such as
the B'nai Brith, by promising not to ally with the FN in exchange
for "an enormous sum of money and exceptional international
support."
</P>
<P>
Le Pen described the passage carrying the quotes as defamatory,
and asked the court to suppress all the disputed passages in its
sample editions being sold, besides demanding a 100,000 francs
(20,000 U.S. dollars) compensation from the book's publisher and
authors.
</P>
<P>
The B'nai Brith has threatened to sue Le Pen for defamation and
anti-Semitism.
</P>
<P>
The 15th Tribunal of Grand Instance of Paris will study the
issue on March 24. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
