<HEADLINE> Egypt Warns of Liquidating Palestinian Problem </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, March 17 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr
Moussa said today that the Arab world would never accept a peace
dictated by Israel, an action that might liquidate the Palestinian
problem rather than solve it.
</P>
<P>
At a press conference at the Presidential headquarters, Moussa
said that most Arab countries are committed to the last Arab
summit statement that peace had to be established on the
principles of the Oslo and Madrid agreements.
</P>
<P>
"Any deviation from this line would mean succumbing to Israel
and would also lead to Arab division," he said, adding that "We
will never accept anything that challenges it."
</P>
<P>
On Sunday Israel vowed to break ground for a new settlement in
Arab East Jerusalem this week.
</P>
<P>
"No matter how great the pressures are exerted on the
Palestinians, to accept a peace dictated by Israel, through
mediation or any other way, will not be acceptable," he said.
</P>
<P>
Asked whether the Gaza international conference held at the
weekend on the Har Homa settlement in Jerusalem would bear
pressure on Israel, Moussa said that international pressure was
actually there but "Israel just did not care about these
pressures."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Moussa denied reports that Palestinian National
Authority President Yasser Arafat, on a visit here early this
month, was so pessimistic about peace talks with the Israelis that
he thought of moving from Gaza to Egypt.
</P>
<P>
He also slammed a threat made by Israel's Justice Minister
Tzahi Hanegbi against Arafat that he faced possible expulsion from
the self-ruled Gaza Strip should a wave of unrest erupts. "It is
extremely insolent," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
