<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-17 20:31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Chief to Sponsor Direct Talks on Cyprus, </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, March 17 (Xinhua) -- The U.N. Secretary-General Kofi
Annan is determined to call a direct meeting between leaders of
two Cypriot communities before the end of June, according to a
European Union (EU) official.
</P>
<P>
EU presidency representative for Cyprus, Kester Heaslip, said
he himself believed such a meeting between President Glafcos
Clerides and Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf Denktash to solve the
protracted Cyprus problem is possible.
</P>
<P>
Heaslip is currently in Cyprus to attend the 11th meeting of
the EU-Cyprus Joint Parliamentary Committee on the Cyprus issue.
</P>
<P>
Annan "is very determined" to see the two leaders meeting
before the end of June, he said.
</P>
<P>
Last week the U.N. Chief's Resident Representative in Cyprus
Gustave Feissel began indirect talks through bi-weekly separate
meetings with Clerides and Denktash to break current deadlock and
pave the way for face-to-face talks.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has remained divided since 1974 when Turkish troops
occupied 37 percent of the island in the wake of a short-lived
Greek Cypriot coup seeking union with Greece.
</P>
<P>
The U.N.-sponsored peace talks aimed at reuniting the island
under a bizonal and bicommunal federal state, have been held on
and off for the past 23 years, but so far no tangible results have
been achieved.
</P>
<P>
Clerides and Denktash have not met sine October 1994 when the
two men held two round of informal talks in Nicosia under the
U.N. auspicies, which reached a deadlock. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
