<HEADLINE> Four Killed, 30 Wounded in Car Bomb Attacks in Algiers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ALGIERS, March 17 (Xinhua) -- Four people were killed and about
30 wounded this afternoon in the Algerian capital in three car
bomb attacks which were apparently staged by Islamic militants.
</P>
<P>
The state radio quoted a communique of Algerian security forces
as saying that soldiers were immediately dispatched to the scenes
of the attacks to rescue the victims.
</P>
<P>
This is the first time in two months for Algiers to be again
subjected to terrorist attacks, after the militant Armed Islamic
Group (sIA) carried out a spate of attacks in the capital from
December 23, 1996 to January 21, killing 48 people and wounding
more than 200.
</P>
<P>
The bombings coincided with an extensive operation being
launched by the Algerian army against the members of the GIA in
the central Algerois region and in Algiers, which was in
preparation for the country's legislative elections scheduled for
June 5.
</P>
<P>
The explosions, which took place separately within one hour,
hit the popular district of Kouba from 15:00 local time (1400
GMT), according to witnesses.
</P>
<P>
A bus stop highly frequented by local people in Ben Omar, near
Kouba, was targeted, while two other bombs blew up beside a house
in the town of Coopemad of the Anassers district and by a road in
the same district.
</P>
<P>
The GIA announced on February 22 in a fax sent to the Arabic
language newspaper Al-Hayat that it would start a "new phase" of
war to "cut the throat of all the apostates and their allies in
the cities and in the villages." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
