<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Manila, Muslim Rebels Urged to Reach Ceasefire Accord </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, March 18 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine military and the
Moro Islamic Liberation Front (MILF) were urged today to reach an
overall ceasefire agreement following the resumption of
hostilities in Buldon, Maguindanao province in the southern
Philippines.
</P>
<P>
Government chief peace negotiator Fortunato Abat said that
instead of blaming each other of who first violated local
ceasefire, the two sides should start to talk about the general
cessation of hostilities.
</P>
<P>
Abat suggested a sub-committee meeting be held immediately
before the scheduled third round of low-level talks between the
two sides in April to include the general cessation matter in the
proposed agenda of both panels.
</P>
<P>
At least three government soldiers were killed in mortar
attacks launched by MILF rebels last Saturday and Sunday against a
military detachment located in Buldon.
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, Al Haj Murad, MILF vice-chairman for
military affairs, said that a teacher and 10 high school students
were killed inside the MILF's camp by government troops.
</P>
<P>
Murad added that the MILF is waiting for appropriate actions
from the government to address properly the latest rash of
atrocities in Buldon.
</P>
<P>
The MILF is a breakaway faction of the mainstream Moro National
Liberation Front, which signed a peace agreement with the
government last year.
</P>
<P>
The government and the MILF had held two rounds of preliminary
talks since the beginning of the year. They have agreed to form a
third independent party to oversee the temporary ceasefire between
the two sides.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
