<HEADLINE> ESCAP Marks Fiftieth Anniversary in Shanghai (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, March 18 (Xinhua) -- The United Nation's Economic and
Social Commission for Asia and the Pacific (ESCAP) marked its
fiftieth anniversary by holding an international symposium here
today.
</P>
<P>
The three-day symposium, under the theme of "development
challenges and opportunities for Asia and the Pacific in the 21st
century and the role of the ESCAP," will discuss such issues as
development of human resources, environment and sustainable
development, trade and investment. It is attended by over 100
delegates from members and alternative members of the ESCAP,
including Japan, Thailand, Malaysia, Chile, Singapore and India.
</P>
<P>
During the symposium, the delegates will visit the historical
site of the ESCAP office and the Pudong New Area in Shanghai.
</P>
<P>
Half a century ago, the UN set up in Shanghai the Economic
Commission for Asia and the Far East (ECAFE), the predecessor of
the ESCAP.
</P>
<P>
In his keynote speech at the opening of the symposium, Chinese
Vice-Premier and Foreign Minister Qian Qichen said that in the
past five decades, after winning political independence, more and
more developing countries in Asia and the Pacific have embarked on
an independent development road and begun their economic takeoff.
</P>
<P>
By the early 1990s, the per capita GNP of some major developing
countries in this region had exceeded 2,000 US dollars, he
said. In 1995, the export of the goods manufactured in Asia took
40 percent of the world's total, exceeding that of Western Europe
and North America combined.
</P>
<P>
In the past ten years or more, he said, the economies of Asian
countries have enjoyed an annual average economic growth rate of
8.1 percent, four times that of the developed countries in the
same period. Asia, and East Asia in particular, has become one of
the areas with the most dynamic and fastest growing economy in the
world.
</P>
<P>
He said that the convocation of the Asia-Europe Meeting last
year reflected a historic change in Asia-Europe relationship and
the move of the world toward multipolarity. It further enhanced
economic links among the two continents and ended the past unequal
relationship between Asian and European states.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970318.0062 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ESCAP Marks Fiftieth Anniversary in Shanghai (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Qian said that the ESCAP brings together 3.2 billion people
with different development levels, political and social systems
and cultural traditions. As the oldest inter-governmental
organization for multilateral economic and political cooperation
with the broadest representation, the ESCAP has played a unique
role in promoting development in the Asia-Pacific region.
</P>
<P>
He said that today, with necessary reform in light of the
actual needs, the ESCAP will gain fresh vitality and improved
efficiency, and will make even greater contribution to the
economic and social development in the region.
</P>
<P>
He said that China has for years supported the ESCAP in its
work and received useful help from the ESCAP in carrying forward
its economic development and the reform and opening up
program. The two sides have maintained a good relationship of
cooperation. In future, China will unswervingly adhere to the
policy of reform and opening-up, make new efforts and enhance
cooperation in all fields with the ESCAP and its members.
</P>
<P>
Adrianus Mooy, executive secretary of the ESCAP, said at the
opening of the symposium that as the unique intergovernmental
forum covering the vast Asia-Pacific region, the ESCAP has forged
a sense of regional identity through its efforts.
</P>
<P>
"As we look ahead, I have every confidence that ESCAP's role in
promoting regional cooperation in the economic and social fields
will be further strengthened and reinforced," he said.
</P>
<P>
Li Zhaoxing, China's vice-minister of foreign affairs, made a
theme speech under the title of "work together for a peaceful,
stable and prosperous Asia-Pacific region in the 21st century" at
the opening ceremony. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970318.0063 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ESCAP Marks Fiftieth Anniversary in Shanghai (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
He pointed out that as the human being is about to ring in the
21st century, the Asia-Pacific region faces rare historic
opportunities:
</P>
<P>
-- The post-Cold War world in which peace, development and
cooperation have become the major theme provides favorable
external conditions for enhanced economic cooperation between this
region and the rest of the world.
</P>
<P>
-- Asia and the Pacific have entered a period of prolonged
peace and development, which serves as the political foundation
for long-term growth of all countries in the region.
</P>
<P>
-- Rapid economic growth in this region in the past 20 years or
more has brought about the material basis for developing countries
to move to a new high in their economic and social development in
the next century.
</P>
<P>
-- Growing multi-channeled and multi-tiered intra- and
inter-regional cooperation in Asia and the Pacific opens a broad
prospect for mutually beneficial cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Qian stressed that at the same time, the Asia-Pacific region is
facing severe challenges. There are still destabilizing factors in
the region and the economic growth in the region is uneven. Most
countries in the region, where 72 percent of the world's poor
population live, are developing countries. They have a weak
science and technology foundation, and lag behind developed
countries in Europe and America, particularly in such hi-tech
fields as the information technology. As the economy grows, the
restraining factors such as pressure on the environment,
inadequate infrastructure and population explosion have become
more and more salient.
</P>
<P>
He said that how to rise up to these challenges and bring an
Asia-Pacific region of long-term stability and prosperity into the
21st century is a major historic task facing every country in the
region. Experience that can be drawn from the regional countries'
endeavor in the past five decades can be summed up as follows:
</P>
<P>
-- First and foremost, peace must be maintained. Without peace
and stability, economic development means nothing but empty
rhetoric.
</P>
<P>
-- Countries should adopt a road of development suitable to
their respective national conditions, and this is the basis for
successful economic development in the region.
</P>
<P>
-- Diversity in the region should be respected and translated
into a driving force for cooperation.
</P>
<P>
-- Vigorous efforts should be made to promote scientific and
technological cooperation and achieve development through science
and technology. ESCAP members differ greatly in terms of science
and technology level, and they are also highly complementary to
one another. Therefore, they should enhance scientific and
technological cooperation and technology transfer so as to
facilitate common prosperity.
</P>
</TEXT>
