<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-18 15:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran's Speaker Pledges No Interference in Other </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, March 18 (Xinhua) -- Iranian Parliament speaker and
presidential hopeful Ali Akbar Nateq-Nouri today pledged no
interference in the internal affairs of other countries.
</P>
<P>
At a press conference here, the 54-year-old speaker, the most
serious candidate for the 7th presidential elections scheduled for
May 23, declared that he will follow the domestic and foreign
policy of President Akbar Hashemi Rafsanjani.
</P>
<P>
Iran's Constitution bars the present president from running for
a third consecutive term, so the 64-year-old president has to
step down from the office in August.
</P>
<P>
While outlining his foreign policy in the future, Nateq-Nouri
said that Iran maintains good relations with most of the
countries in the world.
</P>
<P>
He denied any problem with the Central Asian states, Pakistan
and Persian Gulf countries regards to the issue of the Islamic
revolution.
</P>
<P>
Observers here say that Nateq-Nouri is now trying to modify his
image from a hardliner to a moderate in the Iranian society and
the world.
</P>
<P>
As to Nateq-Nouri's foreign policy, Mohammad Javad Larijani,
vice-chairman of the Iranian Parliament Foreign Policy Commission,
said at the press conference that Nateq-Nouri has made two trips
to the Persian Gulf, adding that "this means he (Nateq-Nouri)
attaches an enormous importance to the region."
</P>
<P>
He said that Iran and other countries of the Persian Gulf
should have a collective cooperation for security and development.
</P>
<P>
He said that it is the priority of Iran's foreign policy to
expand its ties with Asian countries. 
</P>
