<HEADLINE> WFP Official Leaves DPRK After Inspection </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PYONGYANG, March 18 (Xinhua) -- The executive director of the
World Food program (WFP), Catherine Bertini, left here today after
a four-day inspection in which the WFP agreed to donate 100,000
tons of emergency food aid to the flood-stricken areas.
</P>
<P>
Bertini inspected the flood-ravaged Unpha, Rinsan and Phyongsan
counties in northern Hwanghae Province of the Democratic People's
Republic of Korea (DPRK).
</P>
<P>
The executive director was accompanied by vice-chairwoman of
the State Agricultural Commission Kim Yong Suk, and involved
officials.
</P>
<P>
She toured Unpha Bridge and residential districts nearby
devastated by floods, and was informed of the damage scale.
</P>
<P>
The WFP official also met and talked with farmers at sites for
the rehabilitation of devastated farm lands, which is progressing
with the WFP's assistance. She visited a nursery, a kindergarten
and houses.
</P>
<P>
She said the inspection made her a witness of the catastrophic
consequences of two years of natural disasters.
</P>
<P>
Bertini stressed that for the devastated arable lands to be
restored to the original state, and for provisions to be made to
decrease possible flood damage in future, a lot of work such as
afforestation and embankmenting should be done.
</P>
<P>
She added that the efforts to restore farming and production to
normal required additional food supplies from the world community.
</P>
<P>
In her speech at a banquet given to mark the end of her visit
here Monday, she said the visit allowed her to confirm at first
hand that the materials donated for WFP activities in the DPRK had
been successfully used.
</P>
<P>
It was important, above anything, else to render emergency
food supplies amounting to 100,000 tons as called for by the WFP,
she said.
</P>
<P>
She called once again upon the donor nations and the
international community to give much more humanitarian assistance
for improving the food situation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
