<HEADLINE> Microsoft Joins Legend in Chinese Computer Market Coup (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Charles Stevens, Microsoft's vice president in charge of Far
East operations, said, "We have always taken a close interest in
the accelerated development of the information technology industry
through collaboration with China's PC manufacturers."
</P>
<P>
In 1996, Legend paid a total of 50 million yuan in licensing
fees to Microsoft and other companies so that legitimate software
could be installed in its computers.
</P>
<P>
Legend, which was established in 1984 by 11 CAS computer
experts with an investment of 200,000 yuan, topped the list of
computer companies in sales last year. It had ten percent of the
Chinese PC market in 1996, leading all other major Chinese and
foreign computer manufacturers.
</P>
<P>
Simplified Chinese Windows 95-based Legend systems will also
come with Microsoft's Certificate of Authenticity but with no
price increase for new products, Legend's officials said.
</P>
<P>
"By offering computers with Windows 95 at no extra cost," the
company's vice president said, "we not only ensure the true and
genuine application of legitimate software, but also reduce the
consumer's initial investment and protect the value."
</P>
<P>
Legend last year joined in promoting Pentium-based PC's in
China with Intel Corporation, another major American computer
manufacturer.  
</P>
</TEXT>
