<HEADLINE> Microsoft Joins China's Legend in Computer Market Coup (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 18 (Xinhua) -- The computer software giant
Microsoft bit a profitable chunk out of the Chinese computer cake
by selling 400,000 copies of Simplified Chinese Windows 95, which
are to be used in Legend personal computers from now on.
</P>
<P>
Microsoft reached an agreement with the Legend Group, China's
largest computer manufacturer. That is the largest deal since
China and the United States reached an agreement on intellectual
property rights last March.
</P>
<P>
The deal gives Legend the right to install Microsoft's
Simplified Chinese Windows 95 in its PC's. Legend officials
declined to give the exact details of the contract, saying only
that it will be tied to sales of Legend PC's in 1997 and is
expected to be worth over 100 million yuan (12 million US dollars).
</P>
<P>
"Most important," Li Qin, vice president of Legend, said, "We
can play a part in raising the nation's technology level to
internationally competitive standards."
</P>
<P>
The vice president of the Chinese Academy of Sciences, Bai
Chunli, said that the contract demonstrates the determination of
the Chinese government and enterprises to enforce the intellectual
property rights agreement.
</P>
<P>
The contract also confirms the Legend Group's place as the
first local computer manufacturer to install Simplified Chinese
Windows 95 and to pass Microsoft's "Designed for Windows 95"
test.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
