<DOCNO> XIE19970318.0078 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Philippines Ends Textile Row with U.S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, March 18 (Xinhua) -- After eight months of hard
bargaining, the Philippines and the United States have finally
reached a compromise to end a dispute over a new U.S. rule which
restricts imports of textile products.
</P>
<P>
The agreement was signed in Washington earlier this month by
Antonio Basilio, deputy chief of the Philippine negotiating
mission, and Rita Hayes, chief U.S. textile negotiator, the
Philippine Garment and Textile Export Board said Monday.
</P>
<P>
But the deal has been kept under wraps by Washington in an
apparent bid to prevent other trading partners from demanding
similar concessions, according to officials at the board.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, the United States will take a series of
compensation measures to offset losses the Philippines would incur
by implementing the rules of origin.
</P>
<P>
The deal, which is retroactively effective to January 1 this
year, requires the United States to lift its quotas on competitive
Philippine exports of infant apparel.
</P>
<P>
The deal also allows the Philippines to increase its garment
exports to the U.S. by 60 million U.S. dollars this year.
</P>
<P>
An 11 percent increase will be given to exports of Philippine
garment products classified in Group 2 which includes non-apparel
items such as table cloth.
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, the U.S. will increase by 15 percent annual
quota for certain Philippine products in Group 1, which includes
T-shirts, blouses, jeans, jackets and sweaters.
</P>
<P>
In exchange, the Philippine government agreed to withdraw its
unfair trade practice suit filed in July 1996 with the World Trade
Organization (WTO).
</P>
<P>
In a sign of the government's satisfaction with the agreement,
Escolastica Segovia, executive director of the Garment and Textile
Export Board, said the U.S. concession was "an unlimited
opportunity for local garment exporters to tap."
</P>
<P>
The trade dispute between Manila and Washington erupted last
July when the U.S. unilaterally implemented its new mark of origin
rule for its garment imports in violation of the WTO's own rules.
</P>
<P>
Under the WTO's rules, the U.S. is not supposed to formulate
the mark of origin rule. The WTO is the only international body
entitled to formulate and standardize such rules acceptable to all
members, including the Philippines and the U.S.
</P>
<P>
The WTO's Agreement on Textile and Clothing requires WTO
members to observe common mark of origin rules for garment
products.
</P>
<P>
Under the WTO agreement, the apparel exports to the U.S. are
credited against the quota of the exporting country. But the U.S.
new rule provided that finished garment exports are credited
against the quota of the country that produced the fabric.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. rule requires textile-exporting countries like the
Philippines to obtain export visas from third countries, if
imported fabrics from third countries would be used in making
final garment products bound for the U.S. market.
</P>
<P>
A failure to produce such export visas will serve as ground for
U.S. Customs officials to impound affected shipments.
</P>
<P>
The Philippines, which relies heavily on imported fabrics to
produce garment products, considers the requirement an unfair
trade practice, because third countries are reluctant to issue
such visas which may deduct their own quota garment exports to the
United States.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, the Philippines filed a complaint before the WTO
soon after the United States implemented the new rule on July 1
last year.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. has long been the biggest market for the Philippine
textile products, which are one of the major foreign reserves
earners for the country.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, the Philippines exported 1.67 billion dollars worth of
textile products to the U.S., accounting for 60.8 percent of its
total textile exports that year.
</P>
<P>
According to the Philippine government, the U.S. rule would
deal a heavy blow to its textile industry which employs directly
and indirectly five million workers.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. rule will adversely affect some 50 medium-size
companies exporting home furnishing and made-up textile products,
which account for at least 30 million dollars in export receipts.
</P>
<P>
Unlike Segovia's optimistic reaction to the just-concluded
agreement, trade experts here believed the agreement can only
temporarily end the garment row between the two countries since
most of the concessions granted by the U.S. will last only until
the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
The Philippines will have to re-negotiate with the U.S. to
extend these concessions before the year ends.
</P>
<P>
The experts said the only way to avoid a new trade dispute
between Manila and Washington is to fully implement the WTO's
Agreement on Textile and Clothing.
</P>
<P>
Under this 10-year agreement, developed countries, like the
U.S. and Japan, are committed to phasing out quotas imposed to
developing nations on textile and articles of clothing until the
year 2004.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970318.0079 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Track-Laying Completed on Major Southwest China Railway Line (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUIYANG, March 18 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Premier Li Peng and
Vice-Premier Zou Jiahua attended a ceremony today in Baise City in
the Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous Region to mark the completion of
track-laying on the Nanning-Kunming Railway line.
</P>
<P>
One of the country's key construction projects, the line was
completed more than three months ahead of schedule. It will be
put into use at the end of this year.
</P>
<P>
Workers joined the tracks at 9:39 a.m. at Badu station on the
Nanpan River, on the border of Guangxi and Guizhou Province,
after receiving the go-ahead from Zou, an event that Li described
as "a glorious achievement in China's railway-building history."
</P>
<P>
The 898.7-kilometer Nanning-Kunming (Nankun) Railway starts in
Nanning, capital of Guangxi, and ends at Kunming, capital of
Yunnan. One section of the line runs north to Hongguo, in Guizhou
Province.
</P>
<P>
The Nankun is a single-track electrified line with a designed
speed of 80-120 km per hour, a short-term carrying capacity of ten
million tons and a long-term one of 30 million tons annually.
</P>
<P>
So far, nearly 20 billion yuan has been spent on the project,
with the central government being the largest backer. Also
involved were Guangxi and Guizhou, which contributed 200 million
yuan each, Yunnan, which spent 600 million yuan, as well as a
Japanese loan equivalent to 4.6 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
The line had the largest unit cost of any railway in China,
because geological conditions made construction work difficult,
according to Zhou Zhenyuan, director of the Construction
Department of the Ministry of Railways.
</P>
<P>
"The line is the hardest that has ever been built in the
country" said Zeng Derong, an engineer at the construction
headquarters.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970318.0080 </DOCNO>
