<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yeltsin Rests Before Helsinki Summit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, March 18 (Xinhua) -- Russian President Boris Yeltsin,
recently recovered from double pneumonia, decided to take a
two-day rest before leaving for Helsinki for the summit with his
United States counterpart, Bill Clinton.
</P>
<P>
The president's press secretary, Sergei Yastrzhembsky, said
today that before going to his suburban residence, Gorki-9,
Yeltsin will be briefed for the Russia-U.S. summit by Foreign
Minister Yevgeny Primakov.
</P>
<P>
Primakov returned today from a three-day visit to Washington.
</P>
<P>
During his U.S. visit, aimed at paving the way for the Thursday
and Friday summit, Primakov talked with U.S. leaders including
President Clinton, Secretary of State Madeleine Albright and
Defense Secretary William Cohen.
</P>
<P>
The foreign minister maintained Russia's opposition against the
North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO) enlargement, and
demanded a legally-binding document from NATO which would provide
security guarantees.
</P>
<P>
But NATO only offered a NATO-Russia charter in which Russia
would be given a major role in Europe's security order in the next
century.
</P>
<P>
NATO expansion will be a critical issue at the Helsinki summit,
the 11th between presidents of the two powers.
</P>
<P>
Despite Russia's opposition, the U.S. insists on allowing
applicants to enter NATO as from 1999, and NATO leaders plan to
issue formal invitations to some ex-Warsaw Pact states at the July
summit in Madrid.
</P>
<P>
Both sides hoped to make compromises at the summit but admitted
it would be "tough". President Yeltsin said it "will be the
hardest one in the history of Russian-American relations."
</P>
<P>
Apart from the NATO issue, the reduction of strategic offensive
weapons and economic relations between the two countries will also
be on the summit agenda.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin, hospitalized for double pneumonia on January 8,
returned to Kremlin just over two weeks ago after a five-months
absence following heart bypass surgery last November. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
