<HEADLINE> OAU Chief Arrives in Nairobi for Summit on Zaire </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, March 18 (Xinhua) -- Secretary-general of the
Organization of African Unity Salim Ahamed Salim said here today
that "the time is ripe" for the warring parties of Zaire to
"effectively end hostilities and begin negotiations".
</P>
<P>
He stated that he does not think that Zaire will break apart,
saying that "we are totally committed to the unity, stability,
security and territorial integrity of Zaire."
</P>
<P>
The OAU chief made the remarks to reporters after arriving
here today to attend a regional summit meeting on the Zaire
crisis to be opened on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The summit, to be hosted by Kenyan President Daniel arap Moi,
is a continuation of the peace efforts made before by regional
leaders to find a peaceful solution to the conflict, said Salim.
</P>
<P>
He noted that this particular summit assumes great importance
and comes just a week before an OAU special summit on Zaire
crisis to be held in Lome, Togo.
</P>
<P>
It is expected that the Nairobi summit will be briefed on the
Zaire conflict by African foreign ministers who have made a peace
mission to Zaire and special envoy of the United Nations and the
OAU Mohamed Sahnoun who has been touring to Goma, headquarters of
the Zairean rebels, Uganda, Rwanda and Burundi, he added.
</P>
<P>
The regional leaders are trying to make conditions for peace,
and "it is up to the warring parties to make peace", he stressed.
</P>
<P>
It is reported that Prime Minister of Zaire Kango wa Dongo
will join Zimbabwean President Robert Mugabe, President Paul Biya
of Cameroun, South African Deputy President Thabo Mbaki and
Congolese President Pascal Lissouba at the summit tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
It is the first time for Zaire to attend such a regional
summit meeting on its internal crisis.
</P>
<P>
The third largest African country has refused to be present at
the Nairobi Summit I and II because of the attendance of Uganda
and Rwanda accused of supporting the Zaire rebels.
</P>
<P>
This time, President Moi did not invite the Zairean rebels,
Uganda and Rwanda to the meeting. The rebels led by Laurent
Kabila, advancing on several fronts in Zaire, has refused to end
hostilities before negotiations proposed by the UN and also
dismissed the Nairobi summit as pointless. 
</P>
</TEXT>
