<HEADLINE> Manila Maintains 1st-level Alert on Mayon Volcano </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, March 18 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine Institute of
Volcanology and Seismology (Phivolcs) maintained the first-level
alert on Mayon Volcano after a three-day thorough study and
observation of its activities.
</P>
<P>
Phivolcs volcanologist Eduardo Laguerta said today that the
study found a possible magnetic disturbance and a slight increase
in the overall level of Mayon's activities.
</P>
<P>
These activities include a persistent crater glow, an increase
in the number of earthquakes recorded daily, and an increased
sulfur dioxide output, Laguerta added.
</P>
<P>
Volcanologists had recorded a significant crater glow since
January 21 and a relatively high level of earthquakes that picked
22 events on February 28.
</P>
<P>
They also found that sulfur dioxide emission has increased from
the background level of less than 200 tons per day to around 1,000
tons per day, prompting them to warn residents against entering
the 6-kilometer radius danger zone around Mayon Volcano in Labay
province, the central Philippines.
</P>
<P>
At least 78 people were killed when the volcano erupted on
February 2, 1993.  
</P>
</TEXT>
