<HEADLINE> Syria Wants US to Be Honest Peace Broker </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, March 18 (Xinhua) -- Syrian Labor Minister Ali Khalil
today stressed the importance of the role played by the United
States in the Mideast peace process, urging it to act as an honest
broker.
</P>
<P>
The Syrian minister made the remarks in an interview with the
Cairo-based Voice of Arab radio, following the U.S. move to veto a
U.N. Security Council draft resolution to bar a new Jewish
settlement in East Jerusalem, which has damaged its credibility as
a fair mediator in the peace march.
</P>
<P>
The Syrian minister praised Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak
for stressing the Arab position during recent talks with
U.S. President Bill Clinton in Washington.
</P>
<P>
The Egyptian president said earlier that he took new ideas to
Washington for consultations with Clinton on ways to resume
Syrian-Israeli peace talks. He is expected to brief Arab leaders
on the results of his U.S. trip in a couple of days, according to
the radio.
</P>
<P>
However, the U.S. has not informed Syria so far of any new
proposals on bringing the Syrian-Israeli talks back on track,
said the Syrian minister.
</P>
<P>
No improvement appeared in the Syrian-Israeli talks, which had
been suspended since last February and deadlocked over the fate
of the Golan Heights. Syria asks for a full return of the
strategic plateau for peace with the Jewish state, a request
accepted by the former Israeli Labor government but turned down
by incumbent Prime Minister Binyamin Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
"Syria will only resume negotiations with Israel from the
point they broke off and on the basis of the land for peace
principle," he affirmed.
</P>
<P>
The Syrian labor minister held Israel responsible for the
current stalemate in the peace process, adding that its
insistence on constructing a Jewish settlement in East Jerusalem
means it is pushing the region headway to instability and anarchy.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian-Israeli peace process, which could have run on
track after the Hebron deal, was stuck again over the recent
Israeli decision to build 6,500 homes for Jews and close four
Palestinian offices in East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the Palestinians were also angered by an Israeli
promised withdraw from only 9 percent of the rural West Bank as
the first step of further pullbacks, while the Palestinians
demanded a 30 percent pullout. 
</P>
</TEXT>
