<HEADLINE> Round-up: China Invests Heavily in Ethnic Minority Areas (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 18 (Xinhua) -- During the Ninth Five-Year Plan
(1996-2000) period, China will invest some 800 billion yuan in the
ethnic minority-inhabited areas, according to the State
Nationalities Affairs Commission.
</P>
<P>
The investment will focus on infrastructure and resource
development. A new wave of construction will surge through the
ethnic areas, say analysts.
</P>
<P>
China invested a total of 364 billion yuan in infrastructure
construction and key projects during the Eighth Five-Year Plan
(1991-1995) period.
</P>
<P>
China's ethnic minority-inhabited areas consist of Guangxi
Zhuang, Tibet, Xinjiang Uygur, Inner Mongolia and Ningxia Hui
autonomous regions, 30 autonomous prefectures and 121 autonomous
counties with a combined population of 103 million people.
</P>
<P>
The ultimate goal of the Communist Party of China is to help
all ethnic groups progress together and shrug off backward status,
a senior official said.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese government has made efforts to develop the economy
in the ethnic areas since the founding of the People's Republic of
China in 1949. The development of the economy in the areas and
common prosperity for all ethnic groups are mandated by law.
</P>
<P>
The government has implemented a wide range of preferential
policies, and placed more than 100 billion yuan worth of subsidies
in the ethnic areas in the past several decades.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970318.0090 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Round-up: China Invests Heavily in Ethnic Minority Areas (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
In northwest China, the plural line of Lanzhou-Xinjiang railway
has been completed and the construction of a six billion-yuan
railway running through southern Xinjiang has started. In
southwest China, the track-laying on the 20 billion-yuan
Nanning-Kunming railway completed today. The railway arteries are
expected to greatly improve the macro-economic environment of the
ethnic minority areas.
</P>
<P>
In southwest China's Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous Region,
high-grade highways between Nanning, Wuzhou and Beihai are in
operation. A dozen ports with a handling capacity of 10,000 tons
have been completed in port cities. Five airports are being
renovated or under construction.
</P>
<P>
In the coming five years, some 40 percent of resource
development and infrastructure construction projects and about 60
percent of the foreign-funded projects will be in the ethnic areas.
</P>
<P>
The Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous Region, which accounts for about
one-sixth of the nation's territory, has been listed as a new
growth area of the national economy. In 1996, the central and
local governments spent 12.2 billion yuan embarking on 33 major
projects, covering cotton, petrochemicals, and gas prospecting and
development. The region is expected to become China's largest
cotton base and important non-ferrous metals, petroleum and
natural gas industrial bases in the early next century.
</P>
<P>
In the 1991-1995 period, the central government had put 11
billion yuan in the electric power industry in Inner Mongolia,
which is rich in coal resources. More investment will be made in
Inner Mongolia in the 1996-2000 period.
</P>
<P>
The support from developed east areas in terms of talents,
funds and technology has opened up a bright future for the ethnic
areas. The State Council stipulated last year that Beijing,
Guangdong, Shandong and Tianjin pair up with Inner Mongolia,
Guangxi, Xinjiang and Ningxia to advance the economy of the
latter. And special plans are jointly carried out by various
ministries as well as provinces and municipalities to advance the
economy of Tibet.
</P>
<P>
The overall growth rate of the five autonomous regions has
surpassed the national average, statistics indicate. The growth
rate of the gross domestic product in the regions exceeded ten
percent last year, surpassing the national average level for the
sixth consecutive year. The growth rate of per capita net income
of the farmers in the autonomous regions has also surpassed the
national average level. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
