<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Track-Laying Completed on Major Southwest China Railway Line (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Work on the railway started in December of 1990 and lasted more
than five years. The line climbs from Nanning, which is only 78
meters above sea level, to the Yunnan-Guizhou Plateau, which is as
high as over 2,000 meters.
</P>
<P>
Because of the swift rivers and precipitous mountains along the
line, workers had to build 477 bridges and 258 tunnels with a
combined length of 274 km, a figure that is more than three times
that of the Beijing-Kowloon railway, even though the Nankun is
only a third as long.
</P>
<P>
Two of the engineering feats are the 183-meter-tall Qingshuihe
bridge in Guizhou, the country's tallest railway bridge, and an
underground tunnel built near Xiaoyugu station on the Guizhou rail
section because of the landslides that occur frequently on both
sides of the line, Zhou told Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
"Though expensive and difficult, the line had to be built,"
Zhou said, explaining that it was a Chinese government effort that
gave priority to developing resources and building basic
facilities in central and western areas to boost the economic
growth there.
</P>
<P>
The railway is regarded as China's largest poverty-relief
project of the 1990s. There are 15 million people living in
poverty along the rail line, accounting for a quarter of the
country's total. There are also many ethnic groups living in the
area.
</P>
<P>
The Nankun connects up with the Changsha-Nanning and
Nanning-Fangcheng railway lines in the east and the
Chengdu-Kunming and Guiyang-Kunming railways in the west. When the
ports at Guangxi's Fangcheng, Qinzhou, and Beihai are considered,
the railway will become an important outlet to the sea for
southwest China's inland areas, Zhou said.
</P>
<P>
New regional economies in the southern and western part of
China will be formed by the railway, and opportunities will be
created for provinces to cooperate economically with Southeast
Asian countries, authorities point out.
</P>
<P>
Because southwest China is the country's largest source of
aluminum and phosphate, and is rich in other mineral resources,
the Nankun is expected to be a key "Development Road".
Construction work has begun on the Tianshengqiao hydropower
station in Guizhou's Qianxinan Prefecture, which has an installed
generating capacity of 2.52 million kilowatts, and on the Pingguo
Aluminum Plant in Guizhou. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970318.0097 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Track-Laying Completed on Major Southwest China Railway Line (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUIYANG, March 18 (Xinhua) -- Premier Li Peng and Vice-Premier
Zou Jiahua attended a ceremony in Baise City in the Guangxi
Zhuang Autonomous Region to mark the completion of track-laying on
the Nanning-Kunming Railway line.
</P>
<P>
One of the country's key construction projects, the line was
completed more than three months ahead of schedule.
</P>
<P>
Workers joined the tracks at 9:39 a.m. at Badu station on the
Nanpan River, on the border of Guangxi and Guizhou Province,
after receiving the go-ahead from Zou, an event that Li described
as "a glorious achievement in China's railway-building history."
</P>
<P>
The 898.7-kilometer Nanning-Kunming (Nankun) Railway starts in
Nanning, capital of Guangxi, and ends at Kunming, capital of
Yunnan. One section of the line runs north to Hongguo, in Guizhou
Province.
</P>
<P>
The Nankun is a single-track electrified line with a designed
speed of 80-120 km per hour, a short-term carrying capacity of ten
million tons and a long-term one of 30 million tons annually.
</P>
<P>
So far, nearly 20 billion yuan has been spent on the project,
with the central government being the largest backer. Also
involved were Guangxi and Guizhou, which contributed 200 million
yuan each, Yunnan, which spent 600 million yuan, as well as a
Japanese loan equivalent to 4.6 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
The line had the largest unit cost of any railway in China,
because geological conditions made construction work difficult,
according to Zhou Zhenyuan, director of the Construction
Department of the Ministry of Railways.
</P>
<P>
"The line is the hardest that has ever been built in the
country" said Zeng Derong, an engineer at the construction
headquarters.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970318.0098 </DOCNO>
