<HEADLINE> Situation Under Control in Papua New Guinea: PM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference this morning, Chan declared his
government had just survived one of the nation's worst political
crises.
</P>
<P>
The crisis was sparked by the military chief, Defense Force
Commander Jerry Singirok Monday when he asked the Governor-General
to sack Prime Minister Julius Chan. Singirok said he opposed the
government's hiring of foreign mercenaries to end the nine-year
secessionist rebellion on Bougainville island.
</P>
<P>
In an urgent meeting last night, the cabinet sacked Singirok as
commander of the army and appointed Colonel Alfred Aikung as new
acting commander.
</P>
<P>
A government spokesman told reporters that the situation was
calm but tense because of the soldiers' loyalty to the former
commander.
</P>
<P>
According to earlier reports, the PNG government signed a
contract with British firm Sandline International, which has
provided mercenaries to train PNG troops for use in the
nine-year-old secessionist war on Bougainville island.  
</P>
</TEXT>
