<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Albanian President Seeks European Emergency Aid </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIRANA, March 18 (Xinhua) -- Albanian President Sali Berisha
has asked a high level European mission to deliver medicine and
food to the country in chaos, and to help restore order.
</P>
<P>
"Europe's immediate assistance is extremely crucial for Albania
to overcome current difficulties," Berisha said in a meeting with
the mission Monday night.
</P>
<P>
The delegation led by Dutch roving ambassador Jan Comte de
Marchant et d'Ansembourg, and comprising representatives from the
European Union (EU), the Organization for Security and Cooperation
in Europe (OSCE), and Italy and Greece, flew into Albania earlier
Monday to assess how to best deliver aid to the country largely
gripped by anarchy.
</P>
<P>
Berisha said it was of great importance for Europe to provide
humanitarian goods including food and medicine. He stressed that
it was also necessary to send police troops to Albania to help
distribute aid goods, restore social order and reconstruct
Albania's police force.
</P>
<P>
He asked for Europe's help in re-establishing public
facilities, financial institutions and other infrastructures in
order to stablize the macro-economy and financial markets.
</P>
<P>
In response, Ansembourg assured Albanian authorities of
humanitarian aid, short-and long-term economic and financial
assistance, and help in maintaining public security.
</P>
<P>
Prior to Berisha's meeting, Albanian Prime Minister Bashkim
Fino also asked for immediate aid from the EU in talks with the
delegation.
</P>
<P>
Fino noted that situation throughout the country had calmed
down, that social life was returning to normality, and that the
government was making efforts to improve the situation of airports
and seaports. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
