<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-18 13:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Speaker: Iran to Invite Mubarak for OIC Summit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, March 18 (Xinhua) -- Iranian parliament speaker Ali
Akbar Nateq-Nouri declared here today that Iran is to invite
Egyptian President Muhammed Hosni Mubarak to a summit meeting of
the Organization of Islamic Conference (OIC) due in Tehran in
December.
</P>
<P>
The announcement was made here today by Nateq-Nouri, who is
also the front-runner of the 7th presidential elections scheduled
for May 23.
</P>
<P>
While answering a question posed by Xinhua in a joint
interview in the parliament, Nateq-Nouri said that All Islamic
heads of state will be invited and those include Egypt and its
President Hosni Mubarak.
</P>
<P>
"We expect all of them to attend the OIC summit meeting in
Tehran and this is our natural expectation," he added in the 70-
minute-interview given to Xinhua, the German News Agency (DPA),
the Japanese News Service (Kyodo) and the Korean Central News
Agency (KCNA).
</P>
<P>
A building for holding the summit is near completion at the
Sadabad Palace in the northwestern suburb of Tehran and about 42
heads of state of the Islamic world is supposed to attended.
</P>
<P>
As to the question when Iran will extend the invitation to
Mubarak, the 54-year-old speaker said "the schedule on the
delivery of the invitation is with the Foreign Ministry and it
is their job to decide."
</P>
<P>
He said that the Foreign Ministry will also decide whether
the foreign minister himself or other people to do the job.
</P>
<P>
Observers here noted that Iran is launching an active drive
to seek support from the heads of state from other Islamic
countries for the OIC summit in its capital in a bid to form a
united front among them against foreign powers such as the United
States and Israel.
</P>
<P>
Iranian Foreign Minister Ali Akbar Velayati is currently on
his 10-nation tour carrying messages of President Akbar Hashemi
Rafsanjani to his counterparts.
</P>
<P>
Velayati has been to some of the 42-member-OIC states, namely
Turkey, Malaysia, Indonesia, Uganda, Sudan, Oman and Saudi
Arabia. He is currently in Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
King Fahd of Saudi Arabia expressed earlier his thanks to
the invitation extended by Rafsanjani. But he was reported not to
have promised to come to Tehran for the OIC summit.
</P>
<P>
But, Nateq-Nouri said "We regard King Fahd's response as a
positive one. We anticipate he would take part in the conference
if his health allows."
</P>
<P>
The Iranian speaker said that the gathering of heads of the
Islamic states does not mean "we have planned to conspire
against the United States."
</P>
<P>
"... We plan to get together and talk (with) each other to
make uniform of our policies in an attempt to serve our interests
best," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
