<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Row over Liberia's New Elections Officials </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Lagos, March 18 (Xinhua) -- Dispute over new appointment in
Liberia's elections commission between the interim government
leader and her colleagues has caused concern over the peace
process in the country.
</P>
<P>
On Monday, four of the six members of Liberia's ruling Council
of State published a statement denouncing a decision taken by
council chairman Ruth Perry on new appointment in the elections
commission of the country.
</P>
<P>
In her announcement at the weekend, Mrs. Perry made known the
names of new members chosen for the elections commission and the
appointment of a new commission chairman.
</P>
<P>
According to her statement, the appointee of the National
Patriotic Front of Liberia (NPFL), Gloria Scott, who headed the
commission until now, had been replaced by veteran journalist
Henry Andrews.
</P>
<P>
But no sooner had the statement come than her colleagues,
mainly females on the council, denounced it as a dangerous
manipulation and unilateral decision.
</P>
<P>
No details of the issue are immediately available at the
moment, but analysts noted it would have some negative impact on
the forthcoming general elections slated for May 30 this year, if
not properly resolved.
</P>
<P>
Liberia's existing Council of State was reshuffled last August
when a peace agreement was signed by parties concerned to end the
Liberian crisis in Abuja, capital of Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
Ruth Perry was on the occasion made chairman of the council,
which also comprised major warlords Charles Taylor of NPFL,
Alhaji Kromah of the United Liberation Movement (ULIMO-K) and
George Boley of the Liberia Peace Council.
</P>
<P>
The three former factional leaders resigned their posts of
vice-chairmen of the interim government at the end of last month,
targeting at the presidency in the general elections.
</P>
<P>
The elections commission which had been under the influence of
the former warring factions was to be re-organized following the
requirement of a meeting of foreign ministers of the Economic
Community of West African States (ECOWAS) held in mid-February.
</P>
<P>
According to the ECOWAS foreign ministers, the "independent
elections commission" would comprise seven members, with three of
them each appointed by the three former faction leaders and the
other four each rising from the alliance of seven political
parties, women's organizations, youth organizations and labor and
trade unions.
</P>
<P>
The elections commission would also include technical advisors
from ECOWAS, the United Nations and Organization of African
Unity. But they will not enjoy the power to vote.
</P>
<P>
With the successful disarmament and disbandment of Liberia
factional fighters that ended in January, the peace process has
kept its track.
</P>
<P>
The West African peacekeeping force, known as ECOMOG which
monitored the disarmament exercise, has started redeployment to
ensure that its troops be at all polling stations across the
country during the elections.
</P>
<P>
ECOMOG is also working on a proposal to train about 500
Liberian police personnel who will be available for election
duties during the election period.
</P>
<P>
Despite the good environment to be created by ECOMOG to ensure
free and fair elections, analysts said the row between Mrs. Perry
and her colleagues over the elections commission members should
be appropriately settled.
</P>
<P>
Otherwise, the peace process will be affected, they added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
