<HEADLINE> Cambodia's Funcinpec Party Emphasizes Support for Election </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PHNOM PENH, March 18 (Xinhua) -- The Cambodian Funcinpec Party
today emphasized that it strongly and solemnly supports and
encourages a free and fair elections scheduled for 1998, when the
present National Assembly ends its five-year mandate.
</P>
<P>
The Funcinpec Party, led by the Cambodian First Prime Minister,
Prince Norodom Ranariddh, said, "nobody and no party can interrupt
or hinder the scheduled free elections."
</P>
<P>
The statement was a rejection to the idea of Hun Sen, Vice
Chairman of the Cambodian People's Party (CPP), who warned last
week that there would be no elections if King Norodom Sihanouk
abdicated.
</P>
<P>
Hun Sen also proposed a constitutional amendment that would
force royal family members to forgo their royal status if they
sought office.
</P>
<P>
The Funcinpec statement argued that the constitution has no
clause that prohibits the King from abdicating, and bans any
Cambodian citizen of the royal family from engaging in politics.
</P>
<P>
The Funcinpec statement demanded that the CPP clarify whether
Hun Sen's statement was his own belief as a Khmer citizen, or the
common position of the CPP.
</P>
<P>
At its Extraordinary Congress held in January, the CPP made
clear that it supports the commune and national elections due to
be held, respectively, later this year and next year.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Khmer Nation Party president, Sam Rainsy, also
issued a press release today in opposition to Hun Sen's statement.
</P>
<P>
"Every citizen is entitled to the same civil and political
rights regardless of his or her descent," Sam Rainsy declared.
</P>
</TEXT>
