<HEADLINE> Steel Giant Krupp Plans to Take Over Rival </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, March 18 (Xinhua) -- Five years after a merger with the
Hoesch steel company, German steel giant Krupp is now planning a
takeover of the rival Thyssen steel firm, German television
reported today.
</P>
<P>
Krupp's takeover plan is aimed at resolving its own financial
problems with Thyssen's capital reserve, Thyssen officials were
quoted by television as saying.
</P>
<P>
They also feared that the best parts of their company would be
destroyed and thousands of jobs axed because of the takeover.
</P>
<P>
In protest against the plan, Thyssen workers walked off their
jobs Tuesday morning and planned a demonstration at Krupp
headquarters in Essen later today.
</P>
<P>
Workers at Krupp also expressed their concern about the
development and announced they too would demonstrate against the
takeover bid.
</P>
<P>
With an annual turnover of nearly 39 billion German marks
(about 22 billion U.S. dollars) in 1996, Krupp-Hoesch is the
largest German steel producer, followed by Thyssen with a turnover
of about 24 billion marks. Both companies saw their profits
halved in 1996 because of heavy losses in steel production.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
