<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-18 10:53 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Italian PM Arrives in Lebanon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, March 18 (Xinhua) -- Italian Prime Minister Romano
Prodi arrived here from Damascus, the capital of Syria, this
morning in an effort to upgrade Italy's role in the region.
</P>
<P>
Prodi was received at the airport by his Lebanese counterpart
Rafik Hariri and the two left the airport immediately after the
Italian prime minister arrival for official talks in the
Governmental Palace.
</P>
<P>
This is the first visit by an Italian prime minister to
Lebanon although Italy is Lebanon's biggest European trade
partner.
</P>
<P>
Prodi is also due to have meetings with Lebanese President
Elias Hrawi and House Speaker Nabih Berri and then will hold a
press conference before flying back to Rome from his 10-hour stop
in Beirut, the second and last leg of his trip to the region,
where the Italian prime minister will bypass Israel, which is
normally included in standard diplomatic tours in the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
On the eve of his arrival here, Prodi believed that his talks
with his Lebanese counterpart will be "decisive in laying down
permanently energetic relations" between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with Beirut's An-Nahar daily, Prodi said he
admires the "combative spirit" that the Lebanese people never
give up, and describes Beirut as "the amazing city" which is
"closer to Rome than Berlin."
</P>
<P>
He said his government planned to upgrade its political role
in Lebanon and in the Middle East to a level matching its
position as the number one economic and trade partner.
</P>
<P>
"Italy's political and economic weight enables it to take up
an important role in the peace process and observe the
principles of democracy and the basis of economic development,"
Prodi said.
</P>
<P>
"The Middle East is the flashpoint of the Mediterranean
region," he added. "We want to serve the cause of peace and the
progress in the Palestinian area and Lebanon. We enjoy great
credibility in the region because we are not biased." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
