<DOCNO> XIE19970318.0130 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Helsinki Summit Will Be Tough </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HELSINKI, March 18 (Xinhua) -- The coming U.S.-Russian summit
will certainly be a tough one, due to the big difference between
the two countries over the proposed eastward expansion of the
North Atlantic Treaty Organization.
</P>
<P>
The row over NATO's plan to expand into Central and Eastern
Europe is set to dominate the summit scheduled for Thursday and
Friday in Helsinki.
</P>
<P>
U.S. President Bill Clinton's second-term administration has
listed the alliance's enlargement as a top foreign policy goal,
while Russia has taken blocking the plan as its number one foreign
policy target.
</P>
<P>
Russia has long opposed the expansion, arguing that the move
will create a new divide in Europe following the end of the Cold
War and will militarily threaten its national security.
</P>
<P>
Russia insists on concluding a legally-binding document with
NATO which will provide security guarantees. But NATO only offers
a NATO-Russian charter in which Russia will be given a major role
in Europe's security order in the next century.
</P>
<P>
"A document on the parameters of Russia-NATO relations should
be binding," Russian President Boris Yeltsin told a Finnish
newspaper last week. "We intend to put it to ratification, because
we cannot, on past experience, be satisfied with non-binding
assurances."
</P>
<P>
The United States insists, on the other hand, that Russia has
no veto power on the expansion though Russia has a say in this
matter.
</P>
<P>
Clinton has vowed to allow the applicants to enter NATO as from
1999 and NATO leaders plan to issue formal invitations to some
ex-Warsaw Pact states, most possibly Poland, the Czech Republic
and Hungary, at the NATO summit scheduled for July in Madrid.
</P>
<P>
Diplomats say that Washington will not accept Moscow's demand
that NATO be changed into a political organization.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970318.0131 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Helsinki Summit Will Be Tough </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Both Clinton and Yeltsin have admitted that the coming talks
would be tough. Earlier this month, Clinton told his second
post-inauguration news conference that the summit will be "a tough
debate" since the Russians have reasons "in their own psyche and
circumstances that make it a difficult one."
</P>
<P>
Noting that the differences could be unbridgeable, Yeltsin said
last week that the summit "will be the hardest in all the history
of Russian-American relations."
</P>
<P>
Despite these difficulties, the two sides may make some
progress in the discussion of the charter which will define the
future Russian-NATO relationship.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. has promised that there will be no deployment of
nuclear weapons, nor a military build-up on the territories of new
NATO members, and these commitments might be written into the
future charter.
</P>
<P>
Some Western analysts believe that Russia, for its part, may
have to acquiesce in the expansion behind scenes while continuing
to attack it publicly.
</P>
<P>
On arms control, which is another topic high on the agenda, the
two leaders may pledge to implement START II, the second nuclear
weapons reduction treaty between Moscow and Washington.
</P>
<P>
But it will be difficult for them to start negotiations on a
START III treaty. This is because Russia's Duma, or parliament, is
still unwilling to ratify START II, arguing that the treaty was
signed in 1990 by taking advantage of the weakness of the then
Soviet Union. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970318.0132 </DOCNO>
