<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Deadly Beef Bacteria Found Again in HK </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, March 18 (Xinhua) -- A second beef sample from
Yaohan's Sha Tin store has tested positive for the deadly H7
strain of E-coli O-157 bacteria, according to local media reports
today.
</P>
<P>
The sample was one of 13 taken on March 8 after the local
department of health first detected the killer virus in beef at
the store a week earlier. Other samples taken from different
supermarkets all tested negative.
</P>
<P>
Health officials said that this suggested contamination was
occurring at the store, not the abattoir as first thought.
</P>
<P>
"The most likely thing is that the second E-coli sample was due
to contamination of equipment," a health official said.
</P>
<P>
The health department was quoted as saying that it could not
rule out that some pork might have been contaminated as the same
mincer was used for beef and pork, even though the department
could not find the bacteria on minced pork samples collected
later. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970318.0134 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK Unemployment Rate Drops </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, March 18 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong's seasonal
unemployment rate and underemployment rate for the period between
December 1996 and February 1997 dropped further to 2.4 percent and
1.2 percent respectively, a government spokesman said today.
</P>
<P>
This compares to an unemployment rate of 2.5 percent and an
underemployment rate of 1.2 percent for the period from November
1996 to January 1997.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said overall labor market conditions seemed to
have been tightening in recent months.
</P>
<P>
This is the first time since January 1995 that the unemployment
rate fell below the 2.5-percent mark.
</P>
<P>
Declines in the unemployment rate were observed mainly in the
restaurants and hotels, foreign trade and transport sectors while
the situation in the other sectors remained generally stable.
</P>
</TEXT>
