<HEADLINE> Sierra Leone's Ousted Rebel Leader Charged </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FREETOWN, March 18 (Xinhua) -- Two key members of Sierra
Leone's rebel Revolutionary United Front (RUF) today in separate
interviews described the toppled RUF leader Foday Sankoh as
"unreliable and intransigent".
</P>
<P>
Michael Sandin, one of the four RUF representatives to the
eight-member Commission on Peace, said the change in the RUF
leadship was "premediated as it goes in the right direction
which would usher complete and positive changes."
</P>
<P>
Sandin denied that there was a power struggle within the RUF's
high command.
</P>
<P>
"Sankoh was the only stumbling block and as such there was a
need for him to be changed," he told an independent FM radio
station -- Sky 106.
</P>
<P>
"This was a decision taken at the highest level of the RUF as
it appears Sankoh did not want nor desire peace even though the
rest of the combatants demonstrated their willingness to give
peace a chance," he explained.
</P>
<P>
Appearing in the talk show at the same radio station, another
RUF member Agnes Deen Jalloh said that "after six years Sankoh
has proved unreliable."
</P>
<P>
Deen Jalloh, a former teacher at a training college in the
east of the country, claimed Sankoh wanted to become president of
Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
Asked whether the RUF with new leadship would take up arms if
they are disillusioned in the near future, she said that "we have
vowed not to fight any more."
</P>
<P>
However, the RUF was "disappointed" with the attitude of
government troops, she said, referring to an incident in 1992 in
Bunumbu where returnee civilians were classified as rebel
collaboration and forced to dig their own graves and shot.
