<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sino-Portuguese JLG Convenes 28th Plenary Session </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MACAO, March 18 (Xinhua) -- The Sino-Portuguese Joint Liaison
Group (JLG) discussed five issues concerning the transition of
Macao in its 48th plenary session which started here today.
</P>
<P>
The five issues were the localization of civil service, of law,
the implementation of Chinese as an official language, the
nationality issues of some Macao residents and the "Oriental
Foundation."
</P>
<P>
Guo Jiading, chief representative of the Chinese side of the
Sino-Portuguese JLG, said after today's meeting that some progress
has been scored in the three leading issues of the transition,
namely the localization of civil service, of law and the
implementation of Chinese as an official language.
</P>
<P>
In particular, the two sides have been in good cooperation in
the localization of law, and evident achievements have been made,
he said.
</P>
<P>
"The consultation on the Criminal Law and the Code on Criminal
Procedure were finished," he said. "Based on that, this year we
will step up the process on the consultation of some other leading
laws, including the Civil Law, Code on the Civil Procedure and the
Commercial Law."
</P>
<P>
But he said that was not enough.
</P>
<P>
"There is less than three years time left before the handover
of power," he pointed out. "It is urgent for the Portuguese side
to quicken the process of the handling of the three leading issues
since the current progress lags behind the requirements of a
stable transition and smooth handover of power."
</P>
<P>
In particular, he said the localization of civil servants,
especially of those middle and senior-ranking officials, should
should enjoy high priority. A proper number of Chinese citizens
should assume those duties.
</P>
<P>
"The localization process should be handled step by step and
in accordance with a general plan," he stressed. "It cannot be
solved abruptly in the time just before December 19, 1999."
</P>
<P>
On the question of nationality, the ambassador said that that
question is only referred to those descendents of Portuguese who
were born in Macao. He pledged that they would be free to choose a
citizenship of either China or Portugal.
</P>
<P>
"Their wishes will be fully respected," he said. "They need
not worry and should live on in Macao, and continue to make their
contributions to the prosperity, stability and development of
Macao."
</P>
<P>
Antonio Santana Carlos, Guo's Portuguese counterpart, told
reporters that the Portuguese side has presented a detailed
material to the Chinese side, and that the Portuguese side is
conscientious in the localization process.
</P>
<P>
"The Portuguese side hopes that all localization process will
be finished before it leaves Macao in 1999," he said. "The
government (of the future Macao Special Administrative Region)
will continue to function well."
</P>
<P>
In addition, he said that the Portuguese side hopes to "achieve
good results" in the three leading issues with further exchange of
views and materials under an atmosphere of friendly cooperation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
