<HEADLINE> UNCP, DPN Lead in Nigerian Elections </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Lagos, March 18 (Xinhua) -- The United Nigeria Congress Party
(UNCP) and the Democratic Party of Nigeria continue to lead in
Saturday's local government elections on a party basis.
</P>
<P>
The latest reports said that the UNCP has won the chairmanship of
230 local government areas, out of a total of 464 in 29 of the 36
states, where the results have come out.
</P>
<P>
The DPN is the runner-up with 128 chairmanship seats, while the
other three parties, the National Centre Party of Nigeria, the
Grassroots Democratic Movement and the Congress of National Consesus
lagged far behind with 37, 34 and 35 seats, respectively.
</P>
<P>
A breakdown of the results show that the UNCP leads in 12 states,
including Lagos, Abuja, Kaduna, Delta and other politically critical
states.
</P>
<P>
The DPN is the majority party in seven states, including Oyo, Imo,
Osun, Adamawa, Kano, Zamfara and Sokoto.
</P>
<P>
Stalemate is reported in 147 local government areas, where a
run-off election will be held at a date to be decided by the National
Electoral Commission of Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
As more reports on the elections are hitting the press, there
have been stories of isolated violences and protests over the
results of the elections.
</P>
<P>
In Delta State, a 18-year-old girl was killed while many were
injured in a protest which led to a conflict between the protesters
and the police. In Rivers State, a man was stabbed while voting.
</P>
<P>
But, generally, all the parties, including international observers,
have so far agreed that the election is free, fair and peaceful.
</P>
<P>
The final success of Saturday's election will mark a major
achievement of the military government's transition to civl rule
program, and will inject confidence into other events of the
program scheduled later this year, including the elections of
state assemblies and governors.  
</P>
</TEXT>
