<HEADLINE> Mubarak, Netanyahu Exchange Views Over Phone </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, March 18 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak
and Israeli Prime Minister Binyamin Netanyahu had discussions on
the obstacles of the Middle East peace process over telephone
Monday night.
</P>
<P>
The Egyptian MENA news agency reported today that Mubarak
received the phone call from Netanyahu and they discussed the
difficulties and obstacles confronting the Palestinian-Israeli
peace track.
</P>
<P>
During the discussion, Mubarak asserted the necessity to
implement the Israeli troop redeployment agreement in Hebron and
to find a solution to the situation in East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
According to another report, the Israeli leader informed the
Egyptian president that he had tried to have a meeting with the
Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat Monday on ways and means to save
the peace process, but Arafat turned down the offer.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Mubarak also received a phone call from the
Jordanian King Hussein. The two leaders exchanged views on the
latest developments on the Palestinian track and current contacts
under way on the issue.
</P>
<P>
Tensions have been mounting between the Palestinians and the
Israelis since the Israeli government decided in late February to
build a Jewish neighborhood in the Arab East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
According to the plan, Israelis are to start building the
neighborhood today at Har Homa in East Jerusalem. The Israeli
military authorities Monday night declared the Palestinian areas
from Bethlehem to Beit Sahur a "closed military zone" which lies
close to Har Homa area. And the Palestinians have set up protest
tents on the slope of a nearby hill overlooking the construction
site.
</P>
<P>
On the confrontation, Mubarak Monday said to the Egyptian
Nile TV International that all Arabs, Muslims and Christians
were concerned of what was happening there.
</P>
<P>
"Jerusalem is a very delicate question not only for the
Israelis but also for all Muslims and Christians all over the
world," the president said.
</P>
<P>
"The issue should be dealt with the utmost care due to its
sensitivity and because it might bring out problems which could
lead to complicating the situation," he added.
</P>
<P>
He warned against the Israeli settlement policy and said the
consequences would be very grave. He urged Israel not to be
overconfident by insisting on the policy of building settlements
and said it should realize the reality of the situation and
properly re-evaluate the issue.
</P>
<P>
"Continuation in this policy will not contribute to achieving
a just peace but rather it will lead to violence and very grave
consequences," Mubarak stressed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
