<BODY>
<HEADLINE> GNP Expected to Grow 8 Percent in Philippines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, March 18 (Xinhua) -- The Philippines' gross national
product (GNP) is expected to hit 8 percent in the first half of
1997, the maximum level the government expects to attain by the
end of the year, according to the latest Business Expectations and
Perceptions Survey (BEPS).
</P>
<P>
The BEPS is a quarterly poll covering company performance of
the Philippines from July to December of the previous year and
businessmen's economic expectations for January to July of the
current year.
</P>
<P>
Businessmen in the country expect GNP to grow 8 percent by as
early as the first six months of the year, it said.
</P>
<P>
Last year, the country's GNP grew 6.8 percent, slightly below
expectations but well above the 5 percent recorded in 1995. The
1996 GNP performance was comfortably within the official target of
6.5 to 7.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
Aside from the positive prospects for GNP growth, the survey
said most businessmen interviewed seemed to be fully convinced
that prices of basic commodities and goods will remain stable in
the first two quarters of 1997.
</P>
<P>
The boost in confidence among businessmen in the country could
be traced to the economy's relatively stable situation during the
last six months of 1996 when almost all locally-based firms
experienced hefty growths in income partly due to increased demand
from the domestic market, it said.
</P>
<P>
The survey said 45 percent of respondents agreed that their
gross sales in the second half of 1996 rose significantly from the
previous semester and 37.5 percent of those interviewed reported
slight increases.
</P>
<P>
It said local businessmen were no longer as worried as they
used to be during the economy's fledgling years between the late
1980s and the early 1990s when the economy was still caught in a
boom-and-bust cycle.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970318.0149 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-18 10:37 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Saudi King: Israeli Settlement Plan Violates </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, March 18 (Xinhua) -- King Fahd of Saudi Arabia
has accused Israel of violating the Middle East peace process by
proceeding with the plan to establish a new Jewish settlement in
East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
He told a cabinet meeting in the Saudi capital of Riyadh
Monday night that the Israeli decision runs counter to relevant
U.N. Security Council resolutions and that of the Madrid peace
conference, the Kuwait News Agency (KUNA) reported from Riyadh
today.
</P>
<P>
Fahd said that "the new settlement measures violated the
international community's concession towards maintaining the
demographic and geographic status of Jerusalem."
</P>
<P>
Following its cabinet decision last week, Israel was reportedly
determined to start construction of the new Jewish settlement in
East Jerusalem, which the Palestinians want as the capital of
their future independent state.
</P>
<P>
In accordance with the plan, some 6,500 new housing units are
to be constructed for Jews in Har Homa, also known as Jabal Abu
Ghaneim, of the Holy City, which was occupied by Israel  in the
1967 War with the Arabs.
</P>
<P>
Israel's defiance of the Palestinians' interests and violation
of the U.N. resolutions drew much resentment from the
Palestinians and Arab world, and sparked criticism world-wide
including the United States and some European states.
</P>
<P>
The Gulf Cooperation Council (GCC) states earlier this month
called on the Israeli government to "immediately stop
implementing its dangerous decision to establish Jewish
settlements in East Jerusalem," saying it was a warning that
violence and tension would return to the region.
</P>
<P>
Secretary General of the GCC Jamil Hojeilan said in a
statement earlier in Riyadh that the decision posed a threat to
the peace process.
</P>
<P>
The regional GCC groups Saudi Arabia, Kuwait, the United Arab
Emirates, Oman, Qatar and Bahrain. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
