<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Abacha: Lapses in Council Polls to Be Corrected </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, March 18 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria's Head of State General
Sani Abacha said on Monday that all lapses observed in last
Saturday's local council polls would be corrected to
avoid recurrence in subsequent elections in the country.
</P>
<P>
The government has received reports of some observed lapses,
especially organizational and logistics ones, according to
press reports today.
</P>
<P>
Such lapses will be minimized in the course of Nigeria's
transition to civil rule program, Abacha said when meeting with a
group of Americans observing Nigeria's elections in Abuja, the
capital.
</P>
<P>
The 38-member American election monitoring group has
complained of some problems in certain areas they visited during
the elections, but the group members have unanimously lauded the
polls as free and fair, giving the transition process a pass
mark.
</P>
<P>
Joan Wallace, the head of the delegation, said the lapses
observed were mainly organizational, lack of uniformity in
election procedures and logistics.
</P>
<P>
The secret balloting in which voters had to thumb-print their
ballot papers secretly was observed in some polling centers, but
in most places voting was done in the presence of electoral
officers, said Wallace.
</P>
<P>
Wallace is the leader of the Americans for Democracy in Africa
and was in the country a year ago to observe the local government
elections on zero-party basis.
</P>
<P>
Generally speaking, the election process observed last weekend was
so transparent that "there is no way we can deny the legitimacy of the
process," she added.
</P>
<P>
It is reported that the meeting lasted for more than two hours and
every member of the delegation was allowed to air his or her views
about the elections.
</P>
<P>
The Americans promised to properly brief their government on
their findings and make it see reasons why it should support the
transition program as well as open its door for dialogue.
</P>
<P>
The group, who arrived in Nigeria last Wednesday, comprises
journalists, publishers, religious leaders, political activists
and members of non-governmental organizations.
</P>
<P>
They have been in various parts of the country to monitor the
election.  
</P>
</TEXT>
