<HEADLINE> Xinhua International News Summary at 0900 GMT, March 18 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW -- Russian President Boris Yeltsin Monday approved a
government reshuffle in which most deputy prime ministers were
replaced to deal with the country's social and economic crises,
but all ministers in charge of national security and foreign
affairs retained their posts.
</P>
<P>
TIRANA -- Albanian Socialist Party Chairman Fatos Nano has
called on all his countrymen to support the newly formed national
reconciliation government. He said that President Sali Berisha
should resign.
</P>
<P>
LIMA -- The hostage crisis in Lima has dragged on for three
months but there is no sign of a quick solution. The talks between
the government and rebels of the Tupac Amaru Revolutionary
Movement (MRTA) that is holding 72 hostages have not actually been
broken off but the date of resumption remains in suspense.
</P>
<P>
MOSCOW -- Estonia's new cabinet headed by Prime Minister Mart
Siymann was sworn in. Siymann, who was appointed prime minister
last Wednesday after his predecessor Tiit Vahi resigned over
accusations of nepotism, announced the new line-up on Sunday and
has kept most ministers in their old jobs.
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Tensions are continuing to mount between the
Israelis and the Palestinians over today's projected start of
construction at Har Homa in the Arab East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
BANGKOK -- The Danish government has agreed to provide an
interest-free loan of over one billion baht (about 40 million US
dollars) to support dairy farming projects and agricultural
activities in Thailand, according to Thai Education Minister
Sukhavich Rangsitpol.
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- Russian Foreign Minister Yevgeny Primakov said
following his meeting with President Bill Clinton that Russia
would not change its position on the NATO enlargement despite the
pressure from the West. 
</P>
</TEXT>
