<HEADLINE> Multi-Million-Rand Worth of Smuggled Goods Seized </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, March 18 (Xinhua) -- Millions of Rands worth of
smuggled goods had been seized by the Customs in the past year, but
constituted just a fraction of the products being brought illegally
into South Africa, the local daily the Citizen reported today.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the budget hearngs in the National Assembly on
Monday, South African Revenue Services (SARS) Commissioner Trevor
van Heerden said the customs had been seriously neglected in the
past and needed to be upgraded.
</P>
<P>
Seven tons of clothing seized by the Customs had been sent to
Rwanda, while a tender had gone out for another nine tons to be
exported, said the report.
</P>
<P>
Van Heerden said only 3.5 percent of containers coming into the
country were being inspected in 1996, an improvement compared with the
previous years but well below the international norm of five percent.
</P>
<P>
He also said customs experts from the United Kingdom and the United
States played a major role in advising the SARS on how to beef up
controls at international airports and border posts.
</P>
<P>
An earlier report said the government was planning to launch a
nationwide campaign, including the restructuring of the customs and
exercise department, to wipe out smuggling and improve trade revenue
collection.
</P>
<P>
The government also planned to cut the number of international
airports from the present 36 to about eight, and the border post would
be reduced from 118 to 16.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, SARS Chief Executive Piet Liebenberg said the SARS had
recommended that for import purposes the number of airports and border
posts be limited to 10 and 16 respectively. enditem

=03181002

=03181009
NNNN
18:07 18:08 g # PAB
