<HEADLINE> Iraq calls for Dialogue with Iran on POW Issue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, March 18 (Xinhua) -- Iraq's National Assembly has
called for holding direct dialogue with Iran to tackle the issue
of the Iraqi Prisoners of War (POW), who are allegedly still
detained in Iran, local press reported today.
</P>
<P>
Iraqi newspaper Babel today quoted Khalid el Saedi, Chairman
of the Human Rights Committee of Iraq's National Assembly as
saying that "We appeal to Iran's People's Consultative Assembly
to undertake its legal and humanitarian role and to urge the
Iranian government to end the tragedy of the Iraqi prisoners of
war detained in Iran."
</P>
<P>
"We are ready to conduct a direct dialogue with Iran's
People's Consultative Assembly and have no reservation in this
connection," he said.
</P>
<P>
"We would like to remind the Iranian side that the two
countries are Muslim and neighboring each other," said Saedi,
calling for turning over a new page based on mutual respect
between Iraq and Iraq and non-interference with the internal
affairs each other.
</P>
<P>
El Saedi affirmed that there are no Iranian POWs detained in
Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The issues of the POWs and missing soldiers is the key barrier
to normalizing ties between Iraq and Iran, which fought a bloody
war from 1980 to 1988. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
