<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine Trade Deficit Increases </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, March 18 (Xinhua) -- The Philippines' trade deficit
increased to 1.14 billion U.S. dollars in January this year from
816 million dollars a year earlier, the National Statistics Office
said today.
</P>
<P>
A report from the office showed that the country's merchandise
trade for the first month of 1997 grew by 23.9 percent to 4.53
billion dollars from the year-ago level of 3.66 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
Export receipts went up by 19.2 percent to 1.7 billion dollars
while payments for imports rose by 26.9 percent to 2.84 billion
dollars in January, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Accounting for 14.5 percent of the aggregate value of imports
for January, payments for electronics and components increased by
43.8 percent to 411.73 million dollars from 286.25 million dollars
a year ago.
</P>
<P>
Telecommunications equipment and electrical machinery ranked
second with payments reaching 341.2 million dollars, or double the
year-ago value of 170.7 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
Mineral fuels, lubricants and related materials were number
three as purchases grew by 52.2 percent to 316.63 million dollars
from 208.03 million dollars a year ago.
</P>
<P>
The report showed that the United States emerged as the top
source of imported goods in the month, accounting for 649.02
million dollars or 22.9 percent of the total payments.
</P>
<P>
Exports to the United States amounted to 581.68 million
dollars, yielding a total merchandise trade of 1.23 billion
dollars and thus leaving a trade deficit of 67.34 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
Japan, accounting for 20.1 percent of the total import
payments, was the second biggest source of imports.
</P>
<P>
Singapore was the third with payments reaching 157.34 million
dollars or 5.6 percent of the total, the report said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970318.0163 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-18 </DATE_TIME>
