<DOCNO> XIE19970318.0164 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Backgrounder: Sri Lanka's Local Government Elections </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, March 18 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lanka will hold its
twice-delayed local elections on Friday in all but two provinces
of the country for 238 government bodies, and all election
campaigns will end at midnight today.
</P>
<P>
Nominations were handed in last month from a record 18,586
candidates seeking election to 3,567 seats in 12 municipal, 31
urban and 195 village councils.
</P>
<P>
The last local government elections were held in 1991. The
polls had been scheduled for 1995, but were postponed twice for
security reasons.
</P>
<P>
The coming elections are being held throughout the country
except in the northern and Eastern provinces where a civil war is
going on with the Tamil rebels fighting a 14-year-old war for a
separate state there.
</P>
<P>
There are a total of 9,737,970 eligible and 8,248 polling
centers.
</P>
<P>
Twelve political parties and 136 independent groups are
contesting the elections, but the main battle will be fought
between the ruling People's Alliance (PA) comprising seven
political parties and the main opposition United National Party
(UNP).
</P>
<P>
The current elections are regarded as a test for the PA
government which assumed office in 1994. The government's main
plank during the election campaign has been allegations of 17
years of misrule by the previous UNP government.
</P>
<P>
The opposition, on the other hand, is using its campaign to
highlight a string of broken promises by the PA government to
bring relief to the poor, bring down the cost of living, ensure
media freedom and abolish the executive presidency.
</P>
<P>
President Chandrika Kumaratunga is scheduled to preside over
the PA's final rally in Colombo this evening while the Opposition
UNP leader, Ranil Wickremesinghe, is also due to address the UNP's
rival rally.
</P>
<P>
Since early last month, incidents of election-related violence
including murder, shooting, assault and arson have been on the
rise islandwide. The most serious one occurred on February 11 when
PA District Member of parliamentarian Nalanda Ellawala was killed
in a clash between government supporters and their opposition
rivals.
</P>
<P>
Since early last month, there have been a total of 1,481
complaints of election-related violence from the seven provinces
where the local government elections will be held, according to
the Election Commission.
</P>
<P>
The UNP has made 656 complaints while the PA has reported 597
incidents. Many complaints were also made by other political
parties.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Sirimavo Bandaranaike today urged all parties,
candidates and citizens to ensure that the elections were free of
violence and unlawful activity.
</P>
<P>
In a message on the coming elections, she said, "More
importantly no person or property should be harmed or damaged in
any way in the post-election period."  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970318.0165 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NZ Prime Minister Underlines Importance of Asia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, March 18 (Xinhua) -- Prime Minister Jim Bolger
stressed tonight that New Zealand has much to learn from Asia and
its future is intertwined with that region.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a reception hosted by the NZ Asia 2000 Foundation
to mark the start of the Asian Festival, Bolger pledged that New
Zealand will endeavor to be a good neighbor, a good trading
partner and a good friend of Asia.
</P>
<P>
He emphasized the importance of contacts between the New
Zealand people and the Asian peoples, pointing out that the
festival itself is about people.
</P>
<P>
He noted that about 300 New Zealand schools and many
communities are directly involved in the event.
</P>
<P>
The festival, the biggest ever Asian festival held in New
Zealand, is to last for nine days across the country.
</P>
<P>
Asia 2000 media program manager Jinnifer King said the event
aims to celebrate Asian cultures in ways that bring New Zealanders
and Asian people closer together.
</P>
<P>
The festival will feature art shows, exhibitions and street
performances by Asian artists.  
</P>
</TEXT>
