The Philippine government's chief negotiator, Howard Dee, said
in a press statement that the two parties will sign a number of
documents, including a supplemental accord to the Joint Agreement
on the Reciprocal Working Committees during the talks.
</P>
<P>
Negotiating panels from the two sides also agreed to complete
their work by June 30 to reach a "tentative comprehensive and
acceptable agreement," Dee said.
</P>
<P>
"Upon the approval of their respective principles, these
agreements shall constitute the final peace settlement," he said.
</P>
<P>
Dee said the two panels will continue their discussions on
various issues in the agenda and are expected to reach the first
comprehensive agreement on March 22.
</P>
<P>
The two panels will also tackle the unfinished panel business,
particularly the completion of security arrangements, he said.
</P>
<P>
The NDF, a major leftist party in the Philippines, has been
opposed to the government since it was established in the early
1970s.
</P>
<P>
The group weakened considerably after the government launched a
series of military offensives against its New People's Army during
the late 1980s. Most of the NDF leaders have fled to the
Netherlands. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
