<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Coffee Demand Expected to Outstrip Supply </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, March 18 (Xinhua) -- The Coffee Board of Kenya
predicted that the demand for coffee in the world is expected to
outstrip supply this year, keeping prices high in coming months.
</P>
<P>
In a market report issued here on Monday, the board said that
the main coffee producing countries continue to tighten supplies
while the major consuming countries have a record low stock.
</P>
<P>
The prices are expected to be kept high by a smaller crop from
Brazil, the world biggest coffee producer, the report added.
</P>
<P>
Prices at the weekly coffee auction have been rising and, last
week hit a new record of 357 U.S. Dollars per 50-kg bag
and the new price trend is expected to be maintained in the
coming months, it pointed out.
</P>
<P>
Sources here from the coffee sector noted that prices had
risen sharply at Kenya's weekly coffee auction in recent weeks
due to an anticipated supply shortfalls on the international
market.
</P>
<P>
The current drought sweeping the east African country will
reduce Kenya's coffee production to about 78,000 tons for 1996/97
crop year, the lowest level in four years.
</P>
<P>
In January, the board forecast coffee production at 85,000
tons this year compared to 97,575 tons in 1995/96 and 95,806 tons
in 1994/95.
</P>
<P>
Kenya is Africa's fourth largest coffee producer after Uganda,
Cote d'Ivoire and Ethiopia, according to figures from the
Abidjan-based Inter-African Coffee Organization. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
