<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indo-Bangladeshi Friendship Treaty Expires </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, March 18 (Xinhua) -- Bangladesh's much-talked 25-year
friendship treaty with India quietly expired today while a
high-ranking official commented, "Let there be no song and music
signifying the expiry of the agreement."
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Sheikh Hasina, before coming to power last June,
had announced that her party would not renew the treaty.
</P>
<P>
Foreign Minister Abdus Samad Azad recently said: "The treaty
automatically ceased to exist as it became unworkable after the
emergence of SAARC (the South Asian Association for Regional
Cooperation)."
</P>
<P>
Almost all major opposition parties have spoken against its
renewal. Some top leaders of the largest opposition Bangladesh
Nationalist Party on several occasions have even termed it as an
"agreement of slavery."
</P>
<P>
The treaty between the two neighboring countries was signed
amidst much fanfare and publicity 25 years ago by the then Prime
Minister Bangabandhu Mujibur Rahman, father of Sheikh Hasina, and
his Indian counterpart, Indira Gandhi.
</P>
<P>
Officially called the Treaty of Friendship, Cooperation and
Peace Between India and Bangladesh, the agreement was signed in
Dhaka on March 19, 1972, three months after the country's
independence.
</P>
<P>
During most of the last 25 years, relationship between the two
countries, however, has been frustrated by some controversial
issues such as sharing of common rivers, border crime and
insurgency. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
