<HEADLINE> Africa Urged to Develop Local Technologies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, March 18 (Xinhua) -- Executive Director Mohamed
Abdel-Rahman of the African Regional Centre for Engineering Design
and Manufacturing (ARCEDEM) has said continued lack of capacity to
adapt and develop local technologies in African countries will
continue to impede economic development on the continent.
</P>
<P>
He made the remarks in a speech read on his behalf at a workshop
here on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Because African countries could not develop their own
technologies they spend huge amounts of foreign exchanges on
importing machinery, equipment and spare parts thus draining the
continent's financial resources, he said.
</P>
<P>
Arcedem of Nigeria has designed and developed 30 kinds of
machines and equipment and trained 750 engineers and technicians from
43 African countries in the design and manufacturing of machine
elements and spare parts, production management and productivity
improvement.
</P>
<P>
At the workshop, Zambian Commerce, Trade and Industry Ministry
official Daniel Mauzu emphasized the need for industrial
support institutions disseminating information on new processes and
technologies to quickly establish links with small enterprises.
