<HEADLINE> USAID Budget for African Programs Cut </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, March 18 (Xinhua) -- The budget of the US Agnecy for
International Development (USAID) for African social programs has been
cut by 20 percent, local press reported today.
</P>
<P>
Alex Ross, a senior public health adviser of the USAID Bureau for
Africa, told reporters about the cut in Dodoma, central Tanzania at
the weekend at the end of his two-day tour of the Tanzanian AIDS
Project -- Dodoma Cluster Projects.
</P>
<P>
Ross said that the budget cut, however, did not affect the budget
of the health sector which includes the anti-AIDS and immunisation
programs.
</P>
<P>
Sectors affected in the budget cut were the economic growth and the
education, he noted.
</P>
<P>
The USAID adviser further explained that USAID annually spent
between 15 million and 80 million US Dollars in 30 African countries
in health programs, and worldwide the expenditure stood at 100 million
US Dollars.
</P>
<P>
"The number of Africa countries covered by the USAID financial
support fluctuated as we had to stop assistance to countries with
economic stability or involved in civil wars or coup d'etats," he
said.
</P>
<P>
According to Ross, countries that had ceased to be USAID support
beneficiaries included Zimbabwe, Botswana, Zambia, Burkina
Faso, Togo, Cote d'Ivoire and Cameroun while those not covered by the
USAID support included Zaire, Sudan and Somalia.
</P>
<P>
Among the current USAID beneficiaries are Kenya, Tanzania, Uganda,
Mozambique, South Africa and Malawi.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the USAID adviser said that countries that were most
affected by AIDS were Zambia, Zimbabwe, Uganda, Tanzania and Kenya.
</P>
<P>
While the AIDS growth rate in Zambia and Zimbabwe rose to about 20
percent a year, the rate in Botswana rose by about 10 percent. enditem


