<HEADLINE> Southern African Maize Crop to Rise: SADC </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, March 18 (Xinhua) -- Southern Africa could see a
second successive bumper harvest of maize in 1997 although dry
weather and excessive rains in some parts of the region could affect
production, the local daily the Citizen reported today.
</P>
<P>
A tentative maize harvest of between 16.28 million and 20.50
million tons has been forecast for 1997 compared to 20.34 million
tons last year, the report quoted a latest bulletin by Southern
African Development Community (SADC) as saying.
</P>
<P>
The 1997 crop could be almost double that of 1995 when drought
reduced production to 11.1 million tons, the bulletin said.
</P>
<P>
However, SADC said prospects for a good harvest in South Afrcia,
the largest maize producer in the region, have been dampened by the
intermittent dry spells experienced in many parts of the summer
rainfall region.
</P>
<P>
South Africa could produce a maize crop of between 7.5 million and
9.8 millions tons -- considerably down on the 1996 crop of 9.93 million
tons, the bulletin said.
</P>
<P>
In Malawi, Mozambique, and Zimbabwe, flooding following
incessant rains could also reduce the potential maize yield, the
bulletin said. enditem

=03180759

=03180806
NNNN
16:04 16:05 g # PAB
</P>
</TEXT>
