<HEADLINE> Chinese Naval Ships End Visit to Malaysia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUMUT (MALAYSIA), March 18 (Xinhua) -- Two Chinese PLA Navy
ships left here today for Manila at the end of a three-day
goodwill visit to Malaysia.
</P>
<P>
This is the first time that Chinese naval ships visited
Malaysia.
</P>
<P>
The ships, one missile destroyer and one missile frigate, were
under the command of Vice Admiral Yang Yushu, commander of the
East China Sea Fleet of the Chinese PLA Navy.
</P>
<P>
The ships were accorded a warm welcome upon its arrival on
March 15 at the Lumut port, Malaysia's largest naval base located
in its northwest state of Perak, about 288 kilometers from Kuala
Lumpur.
</P>
<P>
"We come for friendship, we come for promoting mutual
understanding and exchanges, and we come for strengthening the
friendly relations between the two armed forces and especially
between the two navies," Yang said in a written statement upon his
arrival.
</P>
<P>
The visit would surely further enhance the continuous
development of the friendly relations between the two peoples, two
armed forces and two navies of the two countries, he said.
</P>
<P>
During the visit, Yang met Malaysian Navy Chief Vice Admiral
Ahmad Ramli Mohamed Noor in Kuala Lumpur and both stressed the
need for more exchanges of visits between naval ships of the two
countries to strengthen the friendly relations between the two
navies.
</P>
<P>
Welcoming the Chinese naval ships to Malaysia, Ramli said the
visit "opened a new page in the modern history of our relations."
</P>
<P>
Yang also met Malaysian Fleet Operations Commander Rear Admiral
Mohd Hussain bin Tamby at the naval base to exchange views on the
development of their respective navies.
</P>
<P>
Both emphasized the need for promoting mutual understanding and
strengthening friendship between the two navies through exchange
of visits to make contributions to the cementing of friendship
between the armed forces of the two countries.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese naval ships were opened to the public on March 16
for a limited period of three hours but attracted an unprecedented
crowd of about 20,000 people from different parts of Malaysia.
</P>
<P>
A Malaysian Navy officer, Suihimi Mahmood, who served at the
base for 19 years, said in an interview with Xinhua, "I am
surprised to see such a big crowd. Our base received naval ships
from a number of countries like Bangladesh, America, New Zealand,
France and they were also opened to the public, but there were
never so many people as today."
</P>
<P>
He said this showed the deep friendship between the peoples of
the two countries.
</P>
<P>
During their stay, Yang and the commanding officers of the two
ships visited a Malaysian Navy ship which was berthed side by side
with the Chinese ships at the port.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese sailors also had friendship football and basketball
matches with their Malaysian counterparts to promote the
friendship between the two navies.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese ships came here after visiting Sattahib, Thailand.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
