<HEADLINE> Official: Ukraine to Seek its Own Security System </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KIEV, March 17 (Xinhua) -- Moscow's policy toward Kiev was
forcing Ukraine to search for a system that could guarantee its
own security, a Ukrainian official told Interfax news agency today.
</P>
<P>
Some Russian actions and rhetorics were also pushing Ukraine to
decide on integration with Europe, said Vladimir Gorbulin,
secretary of the Ukrainian State Committee of Security and Defense.
</P>
<P>
Gorbulin made the remarks while commenting on an television
interview on Monday night by Ukraine President Leonid Kuchma, who
blasted Moscow's "continued aggressive policy" to Ukraine.
</P>
<P>
The Russian policy, said the president, was driving Ukraine to
abandon its position as a non-aligned country and acquire
membership of the North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO).
</P>
<P>
On his part, Gorbulin said today that there were good prospects
for furthering Ukrainian-Russian relations, and that his country
would explore new ways to resolve existing disputes with Russia.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, an official of Russia's institute of European and
American studies voiced his opposition to NATO's preparation of an
agreement to forge a special partnership with Ukraine.
</P>
<P>
The NATO move, the official reportedly said, was designed to
exert pressure on Russia's long-standing position against the
Western military alliance's eastward expansion.
</P>
<P>
Ukrainian Foreign Minister Gennady Udovenko is scheduled to
visit NATO's headquarters in Brussels on March 20 to hold the
first round of talks with NATO Secretary-General Javier Solana on
drafting the document on the special partnership. 
</P>
</TEXT>
