<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand Injects Huge Funds to Spur Exports </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, March 18 (Xinhua) -- The Thai government has decided
to allocate 25 billion baht (about 1 billion U.S. dollars) to
establish a fund to help the manufacturing sector upgrade
technology and increase exports.
</P>
<P>
The fund, one-fourth of which is to be contributed by the Thai
central bank, will provide needy manufacturers with low-interest
loans through the Export-Import Bank of Thailand and the
Industrial Finance Corporation of Thailand.
</P>
<P>
Thai Deputy Prime Minister and Finance Minister Amnuay Virawan
said Monday that the interest rates for the loans would range from
9 to 10 percent with a repayment period of up to 10 years.
</P>
<P>
The textile and food industries will be the first sectors to
receive the boost to modernize their production, said Amnuay, who
took the initiative to set up the fund.
</P>
<P>
Manufacturers obtaining the loans must seek new technology and
equipment to replace outdated production facilities to compete in
the changing world market, he stressed.
</P>
<P>
According to estimates by the Thai Industry Ministry, the
textile industry in the country alone needs 2 billion baht (80
million dollars) this year for machinery modification and
replacement and it will need more in the coming years.
</P>
<P>
Local newspapers said that apart from the 25-billion-baht fund,
the government is expected to seek 10 billion baht (400 million
dollars) in dollar loans and 5 billion baht (200 million dollars)
from the private sector to nurture the manufacturing sector during
the next four years.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said that with the establishment of the fund, the
Finance Ministry is using its main weapon - soft loan facilities -
to foster the manufacturing sector and seek a new breakthrough in
reviving the country's economy.
</P>
<P>
The Thai government earlier this year put hundreds of billions
of baht in the country's ailing property and finance sectors, but
no improvement has been seen so far, they added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
