<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nuclear Test Ban Organization Launched in Vienna </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
VIENNA, March 17 (Xinhua) -- The newly-established organization
to monitor a worldwide ban on nuclear testing started operation
here today.
</P>
<P>
Wolfgang Hoffmann, executive secretary of the Comprehensive
Test Ban Treaty Organization (CTBTO), is expected to sign an
accord Wednesday with Benita Ferrero-Waldner, Austrian Foreign
Ministry's secretary of state, on setting up a permanent agency in
Vienna.
</P>
<P>
The CTBTO, set up after the treaty was approved at the United
Nations General Assembly in September 1996, is designed to monitor
the implementation of the treaty.
</P>
<P>
The agency, to be funded by treaty signatories, will establish
an international data center and a monitoring network of 300
monitoring stations throughout the world.
</P>
<P>
Some 142 countries have signed the treaty.
</P>
<P>
The treaty will not come into force until all the 44
nuclear-possessing countries have signed it. Thirty-seven of the
44 nations have signed it so far. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
