<HEADLINE> Russian President Approves New Cabinet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, March 18 (Xinhua) -- Russian President Boris Yeltsin
Monday approved a government reshuffle in which most deputy prime
ministers were replaced to deal with the country's social and
economic crises, but all ministers in charge of national security
and foreign affairs retained their posts.
</P>
<P>
A decree signed by Yeltsin on Monday on government changes
unexpectedly named Boris Nemtsov, 37-year-old governor of Nizhny
Novgorod region, as a first deputy prime minister. Yeltsin already
appointed the other first deputy prime minister, Anatoly Chubais,
11 days ago.
</P>
<P>
On Monday, Chubais was also appointed Finance Minister to
replace Alexander Livshits who also lost his position as a deputy
prime minister.
</P>
<P>
The ministers in charge of national security and foreign
affairs who would stay on include Defense Minister Igor Rodinov,
Interior Minister Anatoly Kulikov, Nikolai Kovalyov, director of
the Federal Security Service (FSB) and Foreign Minister Yevgeny
Primakov.
</P>
<P>
Apart from two first deputy prime ministers, the new cabinet
has six deputy prime ministers, as compared with eight in the
former one.
</P>
<P>
The four newly-appointed deputy prime ministers were: Deputy
Economics Minister Yakov Urinson, State Property Committee chief
Alfred Kokh, Communications Minister Vladimir Bulgak who will also
be in charge of science and technology reform, and Oleg Sysuyev,
mayor of the industrial city of Samara.
</P>
<P>
Other appointments on Monday include: Vladimir Babichev as
government chief-of-staff in the rank of minister, but he lost his
post as deputy prime minister; Vladimir Fortov as minister of
science and technology, who also lost his posts as deputy prime
minister and chairman of the State Committee for Science and
Technology.
</P>
<P>
Government sources said the new cabinet is expected to meet at
the end of this week. 
</P>
