<HEADLINE> Athletics Australia Says Capobianco Needs New Evidence </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, March 18 (Xinhua) -- Australian sprinter Dean
Capobianco will damage athletics if he fights a four-year ban for
a positive drug test without new evidence, his national ruling
body said on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Capobianco has said he would apply to the International
Amateur Athletic Federation (IAAF) to have the ban overturned
after repeatedly stating his innocence.
</P>
<P>
But Athletics Australia (AA) said the case has been properly
heard and, as it stands, it would not be in the sport's interests
for Capobianco to further challenge the IAAF ruling, which was
announced in Monte Carlo on Monday.
</P>
<P>
In announcing the ban, the IAAF said Capobianco tested
positive for the anabolic steroid stanozolol at a meeting in the
Netherlands last May.
</P>
<P>
The 26-year-old sprinter escaped an automatic four-year ban
when a subsequent AA tribunal cleared him on the grounds that the
testing procedures had been seriously flawed. The IAAF opposed
that decision. 
</P>
