<HEADLINE> Clinton Agrees to Withdraw Lake's Nomination for CIA Head </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 17 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
today accepted Anthony Lake's request to withdraw his nomination
as director of the Central Intelligence Agency (CIA), CNN reported
today.
</P>
<P>
The report said that Lake, a former national security adviser,
sent Clinton a letter late today, asking him to withdraw the
nomination.
</P>
<P>
A ABC-TV report quoted unnamed White House sources as saying
that Lake was concerned that an assault by legislators on his
integrity, management skills and fitness to head the CIA would
simply continue unabated.
</P>
<P>
Lake is one of the final members of Clinton's second-term team
awaiting Senate confirmation, and the Senate Intelligence
Committee was due to resume its confirmation hearings for Lake on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Lake's nomination triggered three days of tough questioning
last week. The questions included Lake's support for a secret 1994
policy that allowed Iranian arms to flow to Bosnia and his failure
to sell 280,000 U.S. dollars worth of energy stock after being
told to do so to avoid possible conflicts of interest. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
