<HEADLINE> Thai Company to Develop Deep-Sea Port in Myanmar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, March 18 (Xinhua) -- The Sahaviriya Group Corporation
Limited of Thailand is planning to develop a deep-sea port in the
area of Bokpyin in Myanmar's Tanintharyi division to link a
neighboring sea port of Thailand -- Bagn Saphan.
</P>
<P>
According to a memorandum of understanding signed here on
Monday between the Thai group and Myanmar Port Authority, a
feasibility study on the Golden Gateways Project for development
of two sea ports -- one in Thailand's Bagn Saphan on the Gulf of
Thailand and another in Myanmar's Bokpyin area beside the Andaman
Sea -- will be carried out.
</P>
<P>
Today's official newspaper The New Light of Myanmar said
Thailand's Bagn Saphan Port will become the eastern gateway while
Myanmar's Bokpyin Port is to be the western gateway.
</P>
<P>
The two sea ports, after connection by a land bridge consisting
of a highway, a railway and natural gas pipelines, will open up an
ideal avenue for commerce between the Middle East and Europe on
the one hand and the Far East and America on the other, the report
said.
</P>
<P>
The study is expected to be finalized within six months and the
Thai group will build and operate the project under the BOT
(Built-Operate-Transfer) system if proved feasible, the report
said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Tachilek-Kengtung Road in Shan state of Myanmar
bordering Thailand is being upgraded with a Thai loan. The road is
to lead through Chiang Rai up to Bangkok and also be used as a
connection infrastructure to China.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
