<HEADLINE> Indonesian House Passes Bill on Amendment to Budget </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, March 18 (Xinhua) -- Indonesia's House of
Representatives at a plenary session Monday passed a bill on
amendment to the 1996/97 state budget (ending March 31) into law,
parliament sources said today.
</P>
<P>
Finance Minister Mar'ie Muhammad said at the session that the
1996/97 state budget has been amended, adjusting it to more
effective and efficient ways of achieving development targets.
</P>
<P>
The state budget was originally envisaged to balance at 90.6
trillion rupiah (39.39 billion U.S. dollars), but was later raised
to 95.8 trillion rupiah (one U.S. dollar equals 2,340 rupiah),
including the surplus budget of 817.9 billion rupiah (340 million
U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Mar'ie said the higher-than-estimated revenues were due to the
realization of oil revenues, estimated at 40.7 percent higher than
budgeted.
</P>
<P>
"The government thanked the house for its understanding of the
adjustments to the 1996/97 national budget, including its support
to the use of the current year's budget surplus and the use of the
proceeds of the sale of shares of state-owned companies to shorten
the period of payment of high-interest offshore loans," the
minister said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
