<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Backgrounder: Nanning-Kunming Railway </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 18 (Xinhua) -- Though only 898.7-km-long, the
Nanning-Kunming electrified Railway, which completed track-laying
today, is one of the most important railway projects in China's
rail-building history.
</P>
<P>
Linking Nanning, capital of the Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous
Region, with Kunming, capital of Yunnan Province, the trunk line
traverses the three underdeveloped but resource-rich regions of
Guangxi, Guizhou, and Yunnan in southwest China. The rail line is
part of China's strategy to tap the economic potential of the
central and western areas.
</P>
<P>
Connected with several major rails, the new line is a major
passage leading the inland southwest to coastal areas in the
southeast.
</P>
<P>
Known as "China's largest poverty-relief project", the railway
can benefit 15 million people still living under the poverty line,
which is a quarter of the country's total poor population.
</P>
<P>
Over perilous mountains and tortuous waters, the railway
negotiates an altitude differential of more than 2,000 meters. The
20-billion-yuan (2.4096 billion US dollars) railway is considered
one of the most technically-sophisticated railway projects of the
country, a miracle of Chinese railway construction. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970318.0219 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand Introduces Rule to Curb Imports </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, March 18 (Xinhua) -- The Thai cabinet has approved a
rule governing the quality of imported products in a bid to curb
import volumes, the local press reported today.
</P>
<P>
The approval of the regulation proposed by the Commerce
Ministry came at a time when Thailand is opening its market to
more foreign products under its commitment to the World Trade
Organization and regional trade liberalization.
</P>
<P>
Thailand has regulations to identify the quality of products
for export, but no rules to identify the quality of imported
products, officials from the Thai Commerce Ministry said.
</P>
<P>
The new rule will help Thai importers and consumers to receive
quality-guaranteed imported products, they noted.
</P>
<P>
The officials also said that with the new rule introduced,
Thailand will have a bargaining counter in trade talks with those
countries which want to restrict imports from Thailand by
requiring high quality products.
</P>
<P>
The Thai cabinet Monday only approved the principle of the
regulation and the ministry is working on the details.
</P>
<P>
The rule will initially target at those sensitive products like
beans, maize and soy beans, but it will cover luxury goods in the
future, according to the officials.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
