<HEADLINE> H.K. Conglomerate Funds Major Road Construction In North China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENYANG, March 18 (Xinhua) -- A Hongkong conglomerate, Cheung
Kong, has decided to put 895 million yuan (10.78 million US
dollars) into a "second ring road" project in the industrial city
of Shenyang, the provincial capital of Liaoning, in northeast
China.
</P>
<P>
The project, which will cost 1.5 billion yuan, is the largest
urban construction project in Shenyang, and the first road project
in northeast China financed by Cheung Kong, which is owned by the
tycoon Li Ka Shing.
</P>
<P>
The Hongkong investment project will cover construction of an
18-kilometer and a 12-kilometer road and two bridges.
</P>
<P>
The whole project calls for expansion and renovation of 64
kilometers of roads, and the building of five flyovers, seven
underpasses, and 6.2 kilometers of suspended roadway, and is
expected to be completed by the end of November.
</P>
<P>
"The funding indicates that Cheung Kong considers Shenyang a
primary choice in its shifting of investment focus from southeast
coastal cities to the north," according to one source.
</P>
<P>
"If the cooperation proves successful, Cheung Kong will inject
more funds into transportation and environmental projects in
Shenyang," the source added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
