<DOCNO> XIE19970318.0224 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Peru, Ecuador to Hold Talks on Border Dispute </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LIMA, March 17 (Xinhua) -- Delegations from Ecuador and Peru
are due to meet in Brasilia next month for talks to resolve the
remaining border problems between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
The meeting has twice been postponed. The first meeting,
scheduled for January was cancelled as Peruvian Foreign MInister
Francisco Tudela was among the hostages being held by Tupac Amaru
rebels in the Japanese embassy in Peru.
</P>
<P>
The meeting was rescheduled for February but had to be
postponed again because Ecuador's President Abdala Bucaram was
sacked by parliament.
</P>
<P>
Both sides now hope to meet up on April 15, but no detailed
agenda has been made available.
</P>
<P>
The meeting is being brokered by Argentina, Brazil, Chile and
the United States, the four guarantors of the 1942 Rio de Janeiro
Protocol of Peace, Friendship and Limits which was supposed to
settle boundary disputes once and for all.
</P>
<P>
The half-century-old border dispute between Peru and Ecuador
flared up at the beginning of 1995 when the two countries staged a
month-long conflict over a disputed 340 square-kilometer zone in
the Cordillera del Condor, a remote stretch of the Amazon jungle.
</P>
<P>
Scores of soldiers died and hundreds were injured in the
fighting which ended with a truce guaranteed by the U.S., Brazil,
Chile and Argentina.
</P>
<P>
However, the threat of another military conflict hasn't
disappeared as both sides keep accusing each other of troop
incursions, air space violations, arms purchases and
misinformation campaigns.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
