<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Austrian Parliamentary Leader on Austrian-Chinese Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
VIENNA, March 17 (Xinhua) -- Austrian National Council
(parliament) President Heinz Fischer said today he believed
China will enjoy peaceful and stable development, and make
new economic and social progress.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with Chinese reporters before his visit to
China on March 24, Fischer hoped the two countries would resort to
all effective measures to strengthen economic cooperation, expand
personnel exchanges and promote cultural exchanges.
</P>
<P>
He talked about his five visits to China since 1974 and the
1994 visit to Austria by Qiao Shi, Chairman of China's National
People's Congress (parliament).
</P>
<P>
He said these visits showed that long-term, stable and
mutually-beneficial relations exist between the two nations.
</P>
<P>
On his visit to China between March 24 and 29, Fischer said,
"The year 1997 is an important year for China, in which senior
Chinese leader Deng Xiaoping passed away (in February), China will
resume sovereignty over Hong Kong (on July 1), and the Communist
Party of China will hold its 15th National Congress (in October)."
</P>
<P>
"I will see with my own eyes the great changes that have taken
place in China over recent years," he noted.
</P>
<P>
"My biggest hope is to promote bilateral relations through
friend-to-friend dialogue and exchanges," he said.
</P>
<P>
Fischer said that China, with its fast-growing economy, has
become an increasingly important market in the world, and there
are broad prospects for developing economic ties between the two
countries.
</P>
<P>
In addition, there are no outstanding problems between Austria
and China, and Austria respects the choices made by the Chinese
people and China's policies.
</P>
<P>
On the issue of human rights, he said, "We understand that all
nations attach importance to the principle of not interfering in
other countries' internal affairs." 
</P>
</TEXT>
