<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Inflation in Italy to Bottom Out </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, March 17 (Xinhua) -- Economic analysts predicted that the
current downward trend of Italy's inflation rate is likely to
bottom out in the second quarter of 1997.
</P>
<P>
Morgan Staley, of the United States, forecast that the average
inflation rate for the April-June period would be 1.9 percent,
while U.S.-based J.P. Morgan predicted 2.0 percent.
</P>
<P>
Deutsche Bank, of Germany, forecast a year-on-year rate of 1.9
percent in April and 1.8 percent in May and June.
</P>
<P>
Analysts associated with the three prominent institutions said
the inflation in Italy would start to creep up in the second half
of the year on some technical and seasonal factors.
</P>
<P>
However, their estimate for a low point between 1.8 and 2.0
percent still meant that this year's average inflation rate will
probably turn out between 2.2 and 2.4 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
