<DOCNO> XIE19970318.0228 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ukrainian Justice Minister Outlines Corruption Crackdown </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KIEV, March 17 (Xinhua) -- Bureaucrats inherited from the
Soviet era are the main source of corruption in Ukrainian society,
Justice Minister Sergiy Holovaty said at a press conference here
today.
</P>
<P>
But not for much longer. Holovaty said this group will be the
main target of an anti-corruption drive by the ministry in the
summer as part of President Leonid Kuchma's "Clean Hands" campaign
launched last month.
</P>
<P>
He said the best way to rid the civil service of corruption was
by wholesale reform of the government's administrative
apparatus. "If ministries and agencies are not reorganized, they
will continue to be ruled by wholely corrupt mid-level officials,"
Holovaty said.
</P>
<P>
He admitted there was corruption in his own ministry and said
audits of the ministry's central and regional organizations had
revealed many cases of abuse of power.
</P>
<P>
Heads of some organizations had unilaterally increased their
own monthly salaries by nearly 1,000 hryvnas (about 550
dollars). Some used their official positions to secure second jobs
in other organizations and the private sector. But he gave no
further details.
</P>
<P>
Holovaty called for an overhaul of the nation's approach to its
judiciary and blamed lack of government money for the increase in
corruption. "The courts are now treated worse than any sector of
the economy," he said. "Meanwhile, the courts are the third branch
of government."
</P>
<P>
He called on the government to give the judiciary the same
level of support provided to the executive and legislative
branches.
</P>
<P>
Last year, the government allocated just 38 percent of the
money needed by the judiciary, a cut that Holovaty said had
encouraged corruption.
</P>
<P>
He said it is now usual for local officials and businessmen to
buy the loyalty of judges by paying to heat their courtrooms in
the winter or even fund the day to day running of the courts.
</P>
<P>
'Clean Hands' must apply first to the justice system and the
judiciary, otherwise it will end up being all talk and no action,
Holovaty said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
