<HEADLINE> Indonesia, Singapore Agree to Boost ASEAN Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, March 18 (Xinhua) -- Indonesian President Soeharto and
Singapore Prime Minister Goh Chok Tong agreed that ASEAN economic
cooperation should be enhanced and that Cambodia, Laos and Myanmar
should join ASEAN, an Indonesian spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
The two leaders, in a private meeting held Monday on Karimun
island in Indonesia's Riau province, said that with a membership
of 10 countries, the ASEAN (Association of Southeast Asian
Nations) region would be a market of more than 500 million people,
Indonesian State Secretary Moerdiono said last night after the
meeting.
</P>
<P>
Moerdiono said, "500 million is a high figure, higher than the
population of Europe." Economic growth in the ASEAN region was an
average of six to eight percent per year, the official said.
</P>
<P>
ASEAN currently groups Brunei, Indonesia, Malaysia, the
Philippines, Singapore, Thailand and Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
Soeharto and Goh also agreed to further develop ASEAN's
potentials and heighten its member countries' competitiveness,
especially in attracting foreign investment, Antara news agency
reported today.
</P>
<P>
Moerdiono said the two leaders also discussed the future of
intra-ASEAN cooperation and agreed to assign some of their
ministers to make a study on the issue.
</P>
<P>
Prior to the talks, Soeharto and Goh launched a giant marine
and industrial complex.
</P>
<P>
The Karimun Marine and Industrial Complex is the third major
industrial project developed by the Singapore and Indonesia
private sectors.
</P>
<P>
Investment in the complex is expected to reach 142.8 million
U.S. dollars over the next 10 years. About half of it is already
in place in the project's first phase which covers an area of 155
hectares.  
</P>
</TEXT>
