<HEADLINE> Hostage Crisis in Lima Deadlocked </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LIMA, March 17 (Xinhua) -- The hostage crisis in Lima has
dragged on for three months but there is no sign of a quick
solution.
</P>
<P>
The talks between the government and rebels of the Tupac Amaru
Revolutionary Movement (MRTA) that is holding 72 hostages have not
actually been broken off but the date of resumption remains in
suspense.
</P>
<P>
The talks are being supervised by a commission of guarantors
set up to negotiate an end to the crisis and made up of
representatives from the Vatican and the International Red Cross,
the Canadian ambassador to Peru and the Japanese ambassador to
Mexico.
</P>
<P>
The government has declared a preference for a peaceful
solution, as a rescue attempt might cost lives among the hostages
including President Alberto Fujimori's brother, senior government
officials, foreign diplomats and Japanese businessmen.
</P>
<P>
The rebels, who stormed Japanese ambassador Morihisa Aoki's
residence on December 17, have demanded the release of some 400
jailed comrades. They also wanted an end to the free-market
economic policies and more state support for the poor.
</P>
<P>
Fujimori has flatly rejected all the demands, promising not to
storm the building if the guerrillas released the captives and
laid down their weapons.
</P>
<P>
The rebels have insisted they would not surrender until their
comrades were released.
</P>
<P>
The MRTA command appears to be prepared to prolong the crisis,
while relatives of the hostages said that they have gone through
three months of anguish and suffering.
</P>
<P>
The denunciation on March 6 by Nestor Cerpa Carolini, chief of
the MRTA command, that government forces were digging a tunnel to
enter the compound and to annihilate the rebels interrupted the
dialogue initiated on February 11.
</P>
<P>
The guarantors worked feverishly tried to re-establish
communications between the government and the MRTA and even
negotiated a meeting, but Education Minister Domingo Palermo, who
is the government envoy, did not show up.
</P>
<P>
Palermo said conditions were still not ripe for any new
face-to-face contact and demanded that MRTA members clarify
several points.
</P>
<P>
After the 10th round of talks on March 12, the two sides agreed
that a period of reflection was necessary during which the
commission of guarantors will try to come up with alternatives to
make a solution feasible.
</P>
<P>
On March 2, Fujimori visited the Dominican Republic and Cuba to
request political asylum for the rebels occupying the Japanese
ambassador's residence, and Cuban leader Fidel Castro agreed to
offer asylum under certain formal conditions.
</P>
<P>
Nestor Cerpa, however, rejected Fujimori's proposal to allow
the MRTA command to leave Peru. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970318.0232 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Financial Reform in Rural China Under Way </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 18 (Xinhua) -- China will step up the ongoing
reform of its rural financial system in order to reorganize rural
credit agencies into co-operative organizations, China Daily
reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Duan Xiaoxing, deputy director of the State Council
Interdepartmental Co-ordinative Group on Rural Financial
Restructuring, was quoted as saying that the basic tasks of the
reform were scheduled for completion by the end of 1997.
</P>
<P>
Grassroots and country-level rural credit co-operatives are
required to further standardize their operating systems, said Duan.
</P>
<P>
Self-disciplinary units within the co-operatives also need to
be founded as soon as possible to assure the healthy development
of rural co-operative financing, Duan said.
</P>
<P>
China now has 52,000 rural credit agencies which can date back
to 1951. They now support 80 percent of the nation's farmers and
70 percent of all firms in rural areas.
</P>
<P>
China started to reform the sector in 1983, when it found that
as organizations run by the Agricultural Bank of China, they
couldn't operate independently or play a more active role in
financing agricultural production.
</P>
<P>
Two basic steps have been defined by the government to realize
the reform of the rural co-operative financial system, according
to Duan.
</P>
<P>
The first step is to separate rural credit co-operatives from
the ABC, and the task had been accomplished in most of the
co-operatives by the end of last year, said Duan.
</P>
<P>
The second step -- which is what the credit co-operatives are
currently working on -- is to establish a rural co-operative
financial system.
</P>
<P>
Credit co-operatives are structured on the basis of a
co-operative system admit farmers and rural firms as members upon
payment of a set fee.
</P>
<P>
And all fee-paying members vote in co-operative decisions, no
matter the amount of money each contributed, which makes it
different from a shareholding system, Duan emphasized.
</P>
<P>
Credit co-operatives are organized primarily to provide
financial services to their members. However, members can also
earn profits in proportion to their current deposits in the
co-operatives.
</P>
<P>
As Duan explained, much of the reform is devoted to
constructing a democratic management composed of a congress of
members, a board of directors that would elect the head of the
credit co-operative, and a supervisory commission.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970318.0233 </DOCNO>
