<HEADLINE> EU Team Arrives in Crisis-hit Albania </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIRANA, March 17 (Xinhua) -- A top-level mission from the
European Union met Albania's Prime Minister Bashkim Fino for talks
on Monday to try to help the new government for national
reconciliation end the anarchy in the Balkan state.
</P>
<P>
The 11-member team, led by Dutch roving ambassador Jan de
Marchant et d'Ansembourg, flew into Tirana by helicopter from the
southern Italian port of Brindisi.
</P>
<P>
The team's primary task will be to help the Albanian
authorities recover administrative control over the country which
has been engulfed in violent protests for the last two weeks.
</P>
<P>
EU foreign ministers turned down Albania's call for military
intervention but at a meeting on Sunday pledged to help the
country "restore civilian structures and law and order".
</P>
<P>
The European delegation will report back on the composition of
a planned advisory mission of experts on civil reconstruction,
police and military matters and humanitarian and financial
assistance.
</P>
<P>
The team is also expected to visit the west coast ports of
Durres and Vlore, key bridgeheads in any relief aid operation,
during its two-day stay. About 6,000 Albanians have fled across
the Adriatic Sea to Italy from these two ports.
</P>
<P>
Diplomatic sources said no meeting had been planned with
President Sali Berisha, whose resignation has been a key demand of
the rebels who have taken control of several towns in the south.
</P>
<P>
At least 100 people have died in more than a month of unrest
sparked by the collapse of the pyramid investment schemes in which
thousands of Albanians lost their life savings. The protests
mushroomed into a lawless anti-government revolt with widespread
looting of arms from army depots.
</P>
<P>
But there are signs that things are starting to return to a
semblance of normality. Although a state of emergency and a dusk
to dawn curfew are still in effect, shops in Tirana were open
again after five days of turmoil, public transport is running and
public employees obeyed a government order to return to work.
</P>
</TEXT>
