<HEADLINE> China to Standardize Manufacturing, Use of Pesticides </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 18 (Xinhua) -- Chinese health authorities will
working out national guidelines to standardize pest-elimination
approaches and restrict the manufacturing, keeping and use of
pesticides in the country, according to a report in today's "China
Daily".
</P>
<P>
The National Committee for Patriotic Health Campaigns (NCPHC)
-- in co-operation with other state departments in charge of
agriculture, the chemical industry and industrial and commercial
administration - is carrying out nationwide inspections of
pesticides including rat poisons, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The drive is expected to stamp out pesticides that have done
more harm to people than to pests and to recommend some safe
chemicals for the public.
</P>
<P>
The NCPHC's expert committee for pest elimination recently
granted certificates to 25 products. A total of 38 varieties of
pesticides including rat poisons were submitted for approval
during the first-ever action.
</P>
<P>
Anti-epidemic institutes across the country are being asked to
use only NCPHC-licensed pesticides, the newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
A report from the NCPHC said many township units and
self-employeed traders are manufacturing and selling unauthorized
poisons, ignoring bans and warnings against such products from ten
ministries and commissions since 1984.
</P>
<P>
Sixty percent of the 57 rat poisons, which were tested by the NCPHC
last year, were found to contain acutely poisonous chemicals
banned by the state.
</P>
<P>
"Such acute poisons kill relatively few rats as many such
rodents have learned to avoid them. But the widespread use of
unapproved poisons has cost human lives," the newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
From 1989 to 1992, Beijing City, Hebei and other four provinces
registered 164 poisonings including 12 deaths of the people who
ate the pesticides by mistake, it said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
