<HEADLINE> Panama to See Lunar Eclipse on Sunday </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PANAMA CITY, March 17 (Xinhua) -- Astronomy buffs in Panama
will get double treat on Sunday with the simultaneous occurrence
of a lunar eclipse and the appearance of the Hale-Bopp comet.
</P>
<P>
The eclipse will begin at 9.58 p.m. local time Sunday and end
at 1.21 a.m. on Monday, according to the Panama Canal Commission.
</P>
<P>
A lunar eclipse occurs when the earth passes between the moon
and the sun, blocking the sun's rays. But this will only be a
partical eclipse because the earth's shadow won't completely
obscure the moon.
</P>
<P>
At 11.39 p.m. local time, "only a very thin rim will be seen
over the orange face" of the moon, a color that will become
brighter in the shadow of the earth, the Panama Canal Commission
said.
</P>
<P>
The eclipse will be visible to the naked eye but experts say
buffs will get a better view if they use binoculars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
