<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rare Lampblack Ink Found in 800-year-old Tomb </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANJING, March 18 (Xinhua) -- A piece of rare lampblack ink
dating back 800 years has been found in a tomb in Jintan city in
east China's Jiangsu Province.
</P>
<P>
The ink, 13 cm by 2.5 cm by 0.8 cm, bears inscription of
"Youyan" (lampblack) and of the ink maker.
</P>
<P>
It is, according to the experts, "as shining as lacquer and as
hard as jade."
</P>
<P>
Historical records have shown that China's ink-making can be
traced back to the Shang Dynasty (16-11th Century BC) and reached
its peak in the Tang (618-907) and Song (960-1279) dynasties. But
few inks from the peak period remain.
</P>
<P>
The ink was found among over 50 relics in two tombs from the
Northern Song Dynasty (960-1127). The other relics include a
writing brush, a black-glazed vase with plum design, gold earings,
a silver hair pin, a bronze mirror, and different lacquers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970318.0247 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ancient Coins Unearthed in East China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANCHANG, March 18 (Xinhua) -- Some 11,000 ancient coins were
unearthed when a dozen households in a township in the capital of
east China's Jiangxi Province were digging a foundation of new
houses.
</P>
<P>
The bronze coins weigh 29 grams each and date from the Northern
and Southern Dynasties (420-589) and Tang (618-907) and Song
(960-1279) dynasties.
</P>
<P>
Most of them are well-preserved, with inscriptions that can be
clearly discerned.
</P>
<P>
Local archaeologists say that this is the province's first find
of so many well-preserved ancient coins. Why they were buried
together is yet to be determined.
</P>
<P>
Experts say that the find will contribute to the study of
social and economic situation of the area during those dynastic
periods.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
