<HEADLINE> More Foreign Investment for China's Inlands </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LANZHOU, March 18 (Xinhua) -- Foreign investment in
northwestern China's Gansu Province has kept growing for several
years, with more capital going to sectors favored by the Chinese
government.
</P>
<P>
According to local officials, the province approved 122
enterprises with overseas investment and used 85.52 million US
dollars last year. To date, some 1,294 foreign-funded ventures
have been registered in the province and foreign investors have
brought in 850 million US dollars.
</P>
<P>
There are also 137 overseas ventures from 20 countries and
regions that have representative offices in Gansu.
</P>
<P>
The investment has played a positive role in improving local
industries and increasing the use of resources, a local trade
official said.
</P>
<P>
This economically backward province has made an effort to
attract loans from foreign governments for improving
infrastructure and investment environment, and renovating old
enterprises. Last year, the province had four government loans
worth a total of 13.55 million US dollars. Foreign governments
have also made commitments for 150 million US dollars for
infrastructure in Lanzhou, the provincial capital.
</P>
<P>
By the end of 1996, the province had got 45 pledged loans from
foreign governments, totalling 440 million US dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
