<DOCNO> XIE19970318.0249 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Engraved Stones Feature Gods of Spring and Autumn </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XI'AN, March 18 (Xinhua) -- Two 2,000-year-old engraved stones
with images of the gods of spring and autumn have been found in
northwest China's Shaanxi Province.
</P>
<P>
Chinese archaeologists say that the stones are the first of
their kind ever found in the country.
</P>
<P>
The God of Spring, Gou Mang, appears on a 1.03-m-high stone,
and has a human face and a bird's body. His left hand holds a red
sun with a black bird with three legs in it, and his right hand
holds a torch.
</P>
<P>
Green dragons, the symbol of wood, the east, and spring in
traditional Chinese culture, can be found under his feet and
behind him.
</P>
<P>
The God of Autumn, Ru Shou, also with a human face and a bird's
body, was carved on a 0.69-m-high stone. He has a snake in his
ears, a white moon with a toad with three legs, in his right hand
and a compass-like object in his left hand.
</P>
<P>
White tigers, the symbol of gold, the west, and autumn, are
found under his feet and at his back.
</P>
<P>
The two stones were among more than 60 engraved stones found at
13 tombs dating back to the Han Dynasty (206 BC-220 AD) in Shenmu
county in Shaanxi. They portray popular Chinese legends and
stories and were painted in a variety of colors such as pink, red,
white, brown, green, and purple.
</P>
<P>
Details such as human hair, strings on musical instruments,
carriage ornaments, and blood from a dog bite can be clearly seen.
</P>
<P>
According to experts, the find will contribute to the study of
fine arts, legends, music, dance, garments, and architecture of
the period. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970318.0250 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> One in Three Italian Children Live in Poverty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, March 17 (Xinhua) -- One in four Italian households and
nearly one in three children under 15 lived in poverty, a Bank
of Italy report published today says.
</P>
<P>
The proportion of families living in poverty rose by 6.5
percentage points between 1980 and 1993, from 19.4 percent to 25.9
percent.
</P>
<P>
The study, based on Bank of Italy data on family incomes for
1993, found that bigger families are more likely to live below the
poverty line. Of the families living in poverty, 15.5 percent had
one child, 23.1 percent had two children, and 49.5 percent had
three or more children. Single-parent families are particularly
at risk, with 40.3 percent of them living in poverty.
</P>
<P>
The study also noted that the problem was more serious in the
south with more than half of children there living in poverty.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
