<BODY>
<HEADLINE> CPPCC Members Call for Conserving Historical City </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, March 18 (Xinhua) -- Members of Guangzhou City
Committee of the Chinese People's Political Consultative
Conference (CPPCC) have made many proposals over the past few
years for protecting local cultural relics.
</P>
<P>
Guangzhou, the largest city in south China, has a more than
2,000-year history and a great number of cultural relics,
including city walls and imperial palace remains from the Qin
(221-206 BC) and Han (206 BC-220 AD) dynasties, a cemetery of
modern revolutionary martyrs, and old shops and stores that are
still in use.
</P>
<P>
Historical sites have, however, been threatened by large-scale
urban construction work and rapid economic growth over the past
decade. So, to deal with the situation, local CPPCC members
studied the problem, put forward proposals, and helped deal with
parties involved in relics-related disputes.
</P>
<P>
As a result of these efforts, the city government allocated
some 30 million yuan for a local company to move out of a building
used by China's first president, Sun Yat-sen, and to put it under
state protection.
</P>
<P>
A great number of historical sites under city protection have
been renovated and old shops and stores have been given priority
in moving back to original sites under construction.
</P>
<P>
Pushed by CPPCC members, the city decided to allocate some
eight million yuan for conservation of cultural relics and another
three million yuan for cultural relics collections each years,
from 1997 on. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
