<HEADLINE> NZ Company Claims Invents New Engine </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, March 18 (Xinhua) -- A New Zealand company claims
it has invented a new engine which outperforms conventional rivals
by virtually every measure, a local press report said today.
</P>
<P>
"This engine scores on every single aspect you measure engines
on - it's lighter in weight, it's easy and very cheap to make,
it's incredibly powerful, it's very low on emissions and it's
extremely fuel-efficient," claimed co-inventor Graeme Jerkins.
</P>
<P>
A small New Zealand company, Continuous Cycle Engine
Development (CCED), owns world patents and licensing rights of the
product.
</P>
<P>
The report said that two years ago, Ford NZ assessed the engine
and was interested enough to send details on to Ford in Detroit,
the United States.
</P>
<P>
Ford NZ initial inspection showed that the engine "had some
merit."
</P>
<P>
CCED has signed a memorandum of understanding with China's
Sichuan Donghua Machinery Works, which will manufacture the
engine, said the report.
</P>
<P>
Donghua has bought the technology and the deal includes a
licensing arrangement where CCED gets royalties based on the cubic
capacity of each unit produced, according to the report.  
</P>
</TEXT>
