<HEADLINE> Bank Mergers Reach 4.8 Billion Dollars in Latin America </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANTIAGO, March 17 (Xinhua) -- Latin America's banking sector
consolidated last year, with mergers and acquisitions (M&AMP;A) worth
4.8 billion U.S. dollars taking place, a study released today
shows.
</P>
<P>
The deals were made to strengthen banks' capital base and
enable them to face the radically different competitive scenario
which emerged following Mexican financial crisis in 1995, a study
by the Santiago Chamber of Commerce said.
</P>
<P>
Bank privatizations accounted for 16 percent of the value of
the M&AMP;A. European banks were also active on the financial scene,
some like Banco Santander expanding, some cutting back on their
Latin American operations.
</P>
<P>
In Chile, bank M&AMP;As worth 1.25 billion dollars took place last
year, accounting for 26 percent of the total value of bank M&AMP;As in
the region.
</P>
<P>
The most important operations in Chile were: Banco Santander's
purchase of Bancosorno for 495 million dollars and the merger
between the O'Higgins Bank and the Santiago Bank which created an
institution with more than 630 million dollars of assets. 
</P>
</TEXT>
