<HEADLINE> US Woman Attempts to Complete Earhart's Final Flight </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 17 (Xinhua) -- A US aviator took off Monday
on a journey to circle the globe in the same type of plane flown
by Amelia Earhart when she disappeared 60 years ago adventuring
the same feat.
</P>
<P>
Linda Finch, 46, took off at 11:15 a.m. (1915 GMT) from
Oakland, California, east of San Francisco, in a refurbished 1935
Lockheed Electra, one of only two of its kind still in existence.
</P>
<P>
Her 44,240 kilometers trip was to sent her across Brazil,
Africa, India, Australia and the Pacific's Howlett Island -- in
the area where Earhart disappeared in 1937 -- before returning to
California.
</P>
<P>
The Texas mother of three, who has restored and piloted vintage
airplanes for 20 years, worked for two years to modernize the
Electra's engine with the assistance of plans and photos from the
1930s. 
</P>
</TEXT>
