<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, March 17 (Xinhua) -- Gianluca Pianegonda of Italy came
from behind in the past two days to take the overall lead after
Monday's fifth stage competition in the Tirreno-Adriatico cycle
race.
</P>
<P>
The Italian colocked 20 hours 29 minutes and 32 second in the
first five stages.
</P>
<P>
Pianegonda finished the 187-kilometer fifth stage in the same
time as the pack and Italian Robert Petito but, assisted by his
team-mates, managed to pick up a two-second bonus on a day which
saw former world champion Maurizio Fondriest pull out.
</P>
<P>
Italian Andrea Ferrigato won the 5th stage with a time of four
hours 39 minutes and 15 seconds.
</P>
<P>
Fondriest, the 1988 road race world champion, pulled out
complaining of back pains, casting some doubt over whether he
would be competing in the Milan-San Remo classic on March 22. He
had been 11th overall, two minute and 49 seconds behind.
</P>
<P>
Tuesday's hilly sixth stage is 168km to Montegranaro. 
