<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kwan, Lipinski Win Groups in Figure Skating Worlds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAUSANNE, March 17 (Xinhua) -- Americans Michelle Kwan and Tara
Lipinski took their qualifying groups in the World Figure Skating
Championships here on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Kwan had to scale down three jumps but was good enough to top
the 15 qualifiers in the group and advance to Friday's short
program. Saturday's long program ends the competition.
</P>
<P>
Kwan, bidding to defend her world title, is expected to meet a
strong challenge from 14-year-old Lipinski who snatched the
U.S. national championship from Kwan last month.
</P>
<P>
Lipinski looked in top form as she matched her seven-triple
jump performances that she used in winning the American title and
the Champions Series final.
</P>
<P>
Lipinski had another triple loop-triple loop combination --
something no other woman has ever done -- and looked solid on the
others to gain scores in the 5.7-5.8 range with a 5.4 mark.
</P>
<P>
Chen Lu of China, who narrowly lost to Kwan at last year's
world championships, finished a poor 11th with a disastrous
routine during which she singled out at four jumps and fell once.
</P>
<P>
In the men's qualifying on Monday, Todd Eldredge beat Elvis
Stojko in one group in a battle between the world champions of the
last three years.
</P>
<P>
Alexei Urmanov topped fellow Russian Ilya Kulik in the other
group with both completing quadruple jumps.
</P>
<P>
The main competition begins Tuesday with compulsory dances and
the pairs short program. 
</P>
</TEXT>
