<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> South China Passing Local Laws to Boost Market Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENZHEN, March 18 (Xinhua) -- The local legislature of
Shenzhen, China's special economic zone in Guangdong Province that
borders Hong Kong, passed 18 local laws and regulations last year,
and more will be adopted this year, according to a local
legislator.
</P>
<P>
Most of the laws and regulations are aimed at improving the
city's investment environment and improving the socialist market
economy, said Li Guangzhen, director of the Standing Committee of
the Shenzhen City People's Congress.
</P>
<P>
They cover management of the Futian bonded zone, tourism,
unemployment insurance, salaries, professional standards, and
other areas.
</P>
<P>
Li said that another 16 local laws and regulations are expected
to be passed this year, and that several existing regulations will
be revised.
</P>
<P>
In China, only provincial legislative bodies have the right to
enact local laws and regulations, but as a special economic zone,
Shenzhen was granted the legislative right by the Standing
Committee of the National People's Congress in July, 1992. 
</P>
</TEXT>
