<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Meets With Primakov for Summit Preparation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 17 (Xinhua) -- Russian Foreign Minister
Yevgeny Primakov said today following his meeting with President
Bill Clinton that Russia would not change its position on the NATO
enlargement despite the pressure from the West.
</P>
<P>
"Russia will not change its position on the NATO enlargement.
But Russia understands that NATO is real force, and Russia would
like to have normal relations with NATO, which would serve the
cause of normalizing stability in Europe," Primakov said in the
White House driveway after his nearly one-hour talks with the
president.
</P>
<P>
Primakov believed that there should be a document with binding
character so that there could be normalized stability in Europe.
</P>
<P>
He was echoing President Boris Yeltsin, who said Sunday that
Russia had made "enough concessions to the United States," and it
was the "U.S. turn to move in order to preserve our partnership."
</P>
<P>
The Russian president insisted that he would demand a legally
binding treaty barring Western forces from ever deploying in
Eastern Europe.
</P>
<P>
Like Yeltsin, Primakov, while emphasizing the unchanged
position of his country, wished that the United States could make
some change in its position toward the NATO enlargement.
</P>
<P>
"If the U.S. position on this one would change, I would applaud
it," he told reporters.
</P>
<P>
Primakov, who arrived in Washington Saturday for talks with
U.S. officials in preparation for a summit meeting in Helsinki,
Finland, between President Yeltsin and President Clinton, held
discussions with Secretary of State Madeleine Albright and Defense
Secretary William Cohen before meeting with Clinton.
</P>
<P>
State Department Spokesman Nicholas Burns said the
Primakov-Albright meetings were "interesting, cooperative and, in
some instances, productive." Bu he declined to elaborate the
meetings.
</P>
<P>
White House Press Secretary Mike McCurry said after the
Clinton-Primakov meeting that they reviewed issues in three large
areas: European security; the future of arms control; and the
economic engagement that the West has with the Russian Federation.
</P>
<P>
McCurry acknowledged that there was no progress made on the
issue of NATO enlargement as both sides would not change their
position on it.
</P>
<P>
"There's still work to be done," he told reporters. "I can't
imagine that we will solve all the issues that are pending."
</P>
<P>
"There is a substantial amount of work that needs to be done to
clear away the residue of the Cold War period," he said. "A large
part of the work of this summit will be about that."
</P>
<P>
The U.S.-Russian summit has been pushed back on day as Clinton
is still recuperating from a knee surgery. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970318.0273 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-18 </DATE_TIME>
