<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UN Secretariat Stages Comprehensive Structural Reforms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, March 17 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations
Secretariat staged today comprehensive structural and
organizational reforms, with Secretary-General Kofi Annan
announcing the integration into one of three departments for
economic and social affairs.
</P>
<P>
At a press conference, the secretary-general said the new
secretariat arrangements should serve to bolster support for
Africa's development, South-South cooperation and the sustainable
development of small island developing states.
</P>
<P>
"Resources will be reallocated; departments integrated;
administrative costs reduced; functions streamlined; new methods
of work introduced; and maximum performance demanded of all
staff," said the secretary-general.
</P>
<P>
The three departments to be merged are the Department for
Policy Coordination and Sustainable Development, the Department
for Economic and Social Information and Policy Analysis and the
Department for Development Support and Management Services.
</P>
<P>
This is one of the latest efforts by the secretary-general to
reform the United Nations in areas that fall within his
authorities. Previous measures included the creation of a policy
coordination group, an executive coordinator for U.N. reform and
reform groups by all relevant entities.
</P>
<P>
In staging the comprehensive structural and organizational
reform, the secretary-general also proposed a 123 million U.S.
dollar cut for the regular budget for the biennium 1998-1999
compared with the previous biennium. In this connection, he
proposed a reduction of approximately 1,000 posts in the program
budget for the biennium 1998-1999.
</P>
<P>
In addition, he proposed establishment of a new Department of
General Assembly Affairs and Conference Services, integrating
major technical support services for the Assembly, the Economic
and Social Council and their subsidiary bodies.
</P>
<P>
To show more emphasis on development issues, the
secretary-general said he would cut one third of the proportion of
regular budget resources used for administrative and other
non-program costs, by the year of 2001, and make the savings
available for development activities. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970318.0275 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-18 </DATE_TIME>
