<BODY>
<HEADLINE> James Baker Named UN Envoy for Western Sahara </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, March 17 (Xinhua) -- Former U.S. Secretary of
State James Baker was named today as the personal envoy of U.N.
Secretary-General Kofi Annan for Western Sahara
</P>
<P>
There has been long standing conflict between Morocco and the
local independent force of the Polisaria guerrilla movement over
Western Sahara since Spain withdraw in 1976.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman for Annan said Baker would assess whether the U.N.
plan of holding a referendum on the territory's future could be
implemented in its present form, whether adjustments acceptable to
the two sides might be possible or whether other ways of resolving
the conflict could be found.
</P>
<P>
"Mr. Baker is a most distinguished statesman. He enjoys a high
international reputation and commands universal respect. His
appointment has been warmly welcomed by the parties," the
spokesman added.
</P>
<P>
He said Baker expected to visit the region soon for talks with
the Moroccan government, the leadership of Polisario and the
governments of Algeria and Mauritania, neighboring countries
closely involved in the issue. Polisario's main base is at
Tindouf, on the Algerian side of the border with Western Sahara.
</P>
<P>
Baker was secretary of state under President George Bush from
January 1989 to August 1992. He was secretary of the treasury from
1985 to 1989 under President Ronald Reagan and served as Reagan's
White House chief of staff from 1981 to 1985. He is a senior
partner in the law firm of Baker and Botts, with offices in
Houston and Washington.
</P>
<P>
In a statement issued after the announcement of his
appointment, Baker said, "I am pleased to do what I can to help
resolve this issue, and will explore with the parties all viable
options.... I will travel to the area next month for initial
contacts with the parties involved." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970318.0277 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Opposes Military Intervention in Albania: Ambassador </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, March 17 (Xinhua) -- U.S. ambassador in Greece Thomas
Niles today expressed Washington's opposition to any military
intervention in Albania.
</P>
<P>
Speaking in the northern Greek town of Salonika, Niles said the
problem in Albania was a political one which must be resolved
through dialogue among the local political forces and with the
assistance of the governments of neighboring states.
</P>
<P>
"We say no to military intervention by an international force,"
Niles said, describing the situation in Albania as "difficult."
</P>
<P>
"We should be neither overly optimistic nor pessimistic, but
evaluate the situation with a balanced and calm stance and help to
solve the problems," the ambassador said.
</P>
<P>
Niles made the statements on the sidelines of the fourth
business cooperation conference "Greece and the Balkans" which
opened today in Salonika. 
</P>
</TEXT>
