<HEADLINE> Clinton Back to Work </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 17 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
today conducted official business three days after serious knee
surgery.
</P>
<P>
White House press secretary Mike McCurry said the president was
"very vigorous and active" on the first working day since Friday's
surgery to repair a torn tendon.
</P>
<P>
Clinton met with Vice President Al Gore, former Vice President
Walter Mondale and former Sen. Nancy Kassebaum Baker on a new
campaign finance reform initiative.
</P>
<P>
He also was meeting with visiting Russian Foreign Minister
Yevgeny Primakov, addressing the issue of NATO expansion in
preparation for this week's summit with Russian President Boris
Yeltsin.
</P>
<P>
Clinton, described by aides as being in good spirits, was still
using a wheelchair to get around his White House residence,
according to McCurry.
</P>
<P>
One of the president's doctors toured Air Force One today to
make sure the plane accommodates Clinton's temporary handicap for
the summit in Helsinki, Finland.
</P>
<P>
McCurry said things were returning to normal at the White
House. "We're getting back to work now," he said.
</P>
<P>
Clinton is expected to be on crutches for at least eight weeks
and faces months of rehabilitation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
