<HEADLINE> Sudan Accuses Uganda of Launching Military Actions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KHARTOUM, March 17 (Xinhua) -- Sudanese Minister of Foreign
Affairs Ali Osman Mohamed Taha today accused Uganda of seeking a
resolution of its border problems with Sudan in the battlefield.
</P>
<P>
At a press conference here, the Sudanese minister denounced
that "Uganda's aggressions against Kaya and Bazi have clearly
revealed that Uganda is pursuing its aggressive policy towards
Sudan."
</P>
<P>
He returned Sunday from the Ugandan capital city of Kampala
where a meeting of the foreign ministers of Iran, Sudan, Uganda
and Malawi called for by Iran late last week.
</P>
<P>
The meeting had not achieved any positive results.
</P>
<P>
The Sudanese minister said at the press conference that despite
the efforts exerted to activate the situation, matters are still
at a standstill. However, an agreement has been reached on
convening another round of talks in Tehran during the first half
of this year.
</P>
<P>
The policy of Ugandan government in resolving bilateral
differences was categorically rejected, he said.
</P>
<P>
He called upon the Kampala government to withdraw its forces,
saying that the Sudanese rebels with the help of Uganda were in
control of the towns of Yei, Kaya and Bazi as well as other
garrisons as reported by foreign news agencies.
</P>
<P>
Sudan and Uganda have an old border conflict, and Sudan is
accusing Uganda of supporting the Sudanese opposition forces in
their military fight against the Sudanese government troops which
has erupted last January. 
</P>
</TEXT>
