<HEADLINE> Yeltsin to Examine Russia-US Ties at Helsinki Summit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, March 17 (Xinhua) -- Russian President Boris Yeltsin
today voiced his intention to examine the partnership between
Russia and the United States during the summit meeting scheduled
for March 20-21 in Helsinki, according to Itar-Tass news agency.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with reporters, President Boris Yeltsin said
that there have not ever been such a difficult summit meeting
between Russia and the Unites States. The questions to be
discussed at the summit "are of principled character for Russia,"
Yeltsin noted.
</P>
<P>
The president said that he and U.S. President Bill Clinton will
examine "how far" the trust between the two countries has
progressed since th end of the cold war and "to what extent our
partnership is reciprocal."
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin said, "We must be facing each other and say why our
partnership is one-sided, why the anti-dumping restrictions are in
effect against Russia, why, against Russia's wishes, the United
States intends to hold exercises in the Black Sea, why Russia is
not a part of different world structures because of the U.S.
position, why Russia has not been recognized as a country with a
market economy although 70 percent of its economy is now in the
private sector."
</P>
<P>
The president also stressed the necessity at the summit to
discuss the problem of American investments in the Russian
economy, in which the United States "takes the place far from the
first." 
</P>
</TEXT>
