<HEADLINE> UAE Examines Offers for Purchase of Arms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, March 17 (Xinhua) -- The Armed Forces of the
United Arab Emirates (UAE) are considering the purchase of
diverse arms and are examining related offers by certain
countries.
</P>
<P>
This was announced here today by Colonel Obeid al Kutbi,
spokesman of the International Defense Exhibition (IDEX-97) which
opened in Abu Dhabi Sunday.
</P>
<P>
He told a press conference at the exhibition grounds
that the UAE Armed Forces were considering offers for the
purchase of arms for the UAE land, sea and air forces. He said
the outcome would be announced in the course of the IDEX-97 or
sometime later.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman revealed that the UAE Armed Forces had concluded
ever since the IDEX-95 several military contracts worth 2 billion
U.S. dollars for the purchase of arms and equipment.
</P>
<P>
He said that competition was still on among US, French and
British companies for a deal of 60 to 80 warplanes, adding that a
decision by the UAE would be taken at the appropriate time after
thorough examination of the offers.
</P>
<P>
Asked about a possible deal for the purchase of six speed
naval patrol boats, the spokesman said that naval arms and
equipments were under consideration and the appropriate decision
would be taken shortly.
</P>
<P>
The IDEX-97 is currently taking place here and will
probably offer the opportunity for the UAE Armed Forces to
purchase the weapons it needs after careful comparison of the
arms and military equipment from various countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
