<HEADLINE> Rolls-Royce &AMP; Associates to Supply Reactor Plants </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, March 17 (Xinhua) -- Rolls-Royce and Associates, part
of the Rolls-Royce Industrial Power Group, was today nominated
sub-contractor to design and supply the reactor plants for the
Royal Navy's next order for Hunter Killer submarines.
</P>
<P>
Rolls-Royce and Associates will be part of a team of companies
working for GEC Marconi, the prime contractor for the Batch 2
Trafalgar Class submarines, according to a press release here by
the Industrial Power Group.
</P>
<P>
The contract for the nuclear steam raising plant will be the
largest single order ever won by Rolls-Royce and Associates, who
design, supply and support all the navy's nuclear plants.
</P>
<P>
The company would supply three PWR2 plants over the next 10
years together with spares and in-service support, the press
release said.
</P>
<P>
They will be fitted with the latest long-life reactor cores,
designed to operate for the life of the submarine, eliminating the
need for costly reactor refueling.
</P>
<P>
Testing of the first of the new cores will begin at the Vulcan
Naval Reactor Test Establishment at Dounreay in Scotland during
2000.
</P>
<P>
This testing forms part of another major contract awarded to
Rolls-Royce and Associates by the Ministry of Defense last month.
</P>
<P>
John Glanville, managing director of Rolls-Royce and
Associates, said, "The order for Batch 2 Trafalgar is excellent
news. We have an advanced design that represents the optimum value
for money with no compromise in safety and is the culmination of
over eight years of development work." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
