<DOCNO> XIE19970318.0285 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hong Kong Will Remain Stable, Prosperous After </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, March 17 (Xinhua) -- A senior Chinese official in charge
of Hong Kong affairs today assured German businessmen that Hong
Kong will remain stable and prosperous after being returned to
China on July 1 of 1997.
</P>
<P>
In a speech delivered to over 100 German businessmen today in
Bonn, Lu Ping, director of China's State Council office in charge
of Hong Kong and Macao affairs, said that China's commitment to a
stable and prosperous Hong Kong has been clear for quite some
time.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that it is not only in the interests of Hong Kong,
but also in the interests of China as a whole, to practice the
policy of "one country-two systems" in Hong Kong and let "Hong
Kong people govern Hong Kong."
</P>
<P>
"China, in opening its economy to the world, needs a capitalist
enclave like Hong Kong to serve as a window to the Western world,
and vice versa, the Western world can also use Hong Kong as a
bridge to enter into the uncharted market on the mainland," Lu
said.
</P>
<P>
Lu also made it clear that China will hold on to the principles
laid out in the Basic Law of Hong Kong which seek to preserve the
Hong Kong way of life that has been the key to its success.
</P>
<P>
"While some people may have been skeptical about whether those
principles would be fully carried out, I think recent events have
shown those concerns to be unfounded," Lu said.
</P>
<P>
He said that as July 1 is approaching, people are more and more
convinced about the sincerity of the Chinese government in
carrying out the provisions under the Basic Law, which will serve
as a mini-constitution for Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
Lu also expressed the confidence that Hong Kong will remain
attractive for foreign investment and will remain the business
center of Asia and a world-class financial center after 1997.
</P>
<P>
"Political and economic stability, a reliable currency, a sound
legal system, and a favorable tax regime are all important factors
which will allow Hong Kong to maintain its position as a great
place to live in and the best place to invest in," he said. He
added that Hong Kong's stability and new relationship with China
mean that the investment environment will only get better.
</P>
<P>
"Now it is time (for foreign businessmen) to participate in the
prosperity and the economic opportunities that will continue well
beyond July 1 of this year," Lu said.
</P>
<P>
Before making the speech, Lu met with German Minister in the
Chancellor's Office Friedrich Bohl. Both sides stressed the
importance of a smooth transfer of power in Hong Kong in order to
ensure its position as the economic and financial center of Asia.
</P>
<P>
Bohl also stressed Germany's continuing interest in Hong Kong
and expected that his country's economic link to Hong Kong will be
further deepened.
</P>
<P>
According to a survey revealed today by German economic
representative in Hong Kong Ekkehard Goetting, over three quarters
of German companies based in Hong Kong are confident that the
political and economic situation in Hong Kong will remain stable
or even be improved after 1997. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
