<HEADLINE> US Urges Palestinians Not to Resort to Drastic Actions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 17 (Xinhua) -- With Israel and the
Palestinians preparing for a showdown over Israel's decision to
begin building a Jewish neighborhood in east Jerusalem, the United
States today urged the Palestinians not to take any action
involving violence.
</P>
<P>
"There can be no justification for anyone firing a gun or
throwing a bomb," State Department spokesman Nicholas Burns said
at a news briefing.
</P>
<P>
He admitted that the situation in the Middle East "is troubled"
as the Israeli government "is going ahead" with the plan to break
ground Tuesday for 6,500 Jewish homes in historically Arab east
Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
Burns just repeated the U.S. position over the Israeli housing
construction, saying, "We don't think it was a good idea."
</P>
<P>
The Clinton administration has criticized the Israeli
government for the move, but when the issue went up to the U.N.
Security Council, its representative vetoed a resolution to
condemn Israel for its violation of the Israeli-Palestinian
agreement.
</P>
<P>
The General Assembly of the United Nations later overwhelmingly
passed the resolution against the U.S. will. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
